<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: South Lebanon Army Not Ignored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today promised that any peace accord in the
Middle East will take into account South Lebanon Army's (SLA)
interests, state-run Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the pro-Israel SLA Commander General Antoine
Lahad here, he also reiterated Israel's commitment to its ally in
its self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were in an apparent attempt to boost the low morale
of Israel's ally in the Lebanon war.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place amid reports that Israel had recently
initiated a proposal to replace the Israeli army and the SLA in
the "security zone" with an interim force from France, Egypt and
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Paris, Israel relayed the proposal
to Lebanon through French diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Lebanese sources, Syria intends to reject
the Israeli proposal, considered by Damascus as another attempt
to separate the Lebanese and Syrian peace tracks.
</P>
<P>
Syria sees the Israeli proposal as a new version of the
"Lebanon First" idea, broached by the Netanyahu government a few
weeks after its formation and then rejected by Damascus.
</P>
<P>
By proposing the "Lebanon First" plan, the Israeli government
wanted to end hostilities in Lebanon first before tackling the
fate of the Golan Heights which was captured by the Jewish state
in the 1967 Mideast war and Syria wants to take back.
</P>
<P>
Syria accused Israel of trying to distract attention away from
the main issue of the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
