<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York City Reported Safer Than Most Cities in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK,January 6 (Xinhua) -- New York City, known for crime
ridden, is now reported safer than most cities in the United
States, with its ranking down from 136th to 144th in total crime
for the first six months of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to a preliminary report issued yesterday by the
Federal Bureau of Investigation, in the first six months of last
year, New York saw a decline of 0.2 percent compared to a
nationwide decrease of one percent in all the categories except
rape. Burglary declined 15.3 percent in the city while it was
going down 5 percent in the rest of the country. Murder declined
by 11.7 percent in the city while going down 7 percent nationwide.
The report shows that 983 murders were committed in the city for
all of 1996, the lowest in 28 years.
</P>
<P>
The rankings move New York down from its position on the list
of the same period in 1995, in which it is ranked 136th of 182
cities.
</P>
<P>
The city's crime drop goes to the Police Department's new
strategies and to factors like the decline in the crack cocaine
trade and the aging of the baby-boom population.
</P>
<P>
Mayor of the city Rudolph W. Giuliani told a news conference
yesterday that the crime drop in the three consecutive years made
people feel comfortable putting businesses in New York City. That
means increased tourism and jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
