<HEADLINE> Sykora Wins Third Slalom of the Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW January 5 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Thomas Sykora proved he
is the strongest skier by winning his third world cup title of the
season in Kranjska Gora of Slovenia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian skied a near-perfect second run to move up from
the second position he held after the first run. His combined time
after two runs was of one minute, 41.93 seconds.
</P>
<P>
France's 24-year-old Sebastien Amiez, winner of last year's
World Cup slalom title, finished second Monday with a combined
time of 1:42.29 while 1994 Olympic slalom champion Thomas
Stangassinger of Austria dropped to third place.
</P>
<P>
American Matt Grosjean of Steamboat Springs, Colorado, attacked
the course both runs to finish fourth and earn his best ever World
Cup result. Grosjean, 26, started the race with the number 25
start bib, moved up to eighth after the first run and then ended
up fourth.
</P>
<P>
Fifth place Monday went to another Austrian, up-and-coming
Siegfried Voglreiter, who finished second in Sunday's giant slalom
race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
