<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India Agree to Strengthen Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and India agreed today
to strengthen their economic relations and cooperation in
"crucially important areas" including stamping out cross-border
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached by Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina and her Indian counterpart H.D. Deve Gowda in their
official talks here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Deve Gowda arrived this morning for a two-day official visit.
Hasina visited New Delhi in December when the two prime ministers
signed a 30- year treaty on Ganges water sharing between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Today's summit meeting took place in an "extremely cordial and
friendly atmosphere," Bangladeshi Foreign Secretary Farooq Sobhan
told newsmen after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers agreed to take measures to activate the
Indo-Bangladesh Joint Rivers Commission, have the Joint Economic
Commission meet early and have regular contacts between the two
countries to discuss and eliminate the cross-border insurgency,
Sobhan said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides laid special emphasis on the signing of the water
treaty and described it as "historic and a landmark" in bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed bilateral economic and trade
relations and decided to forge sub-regional cooperation involving
Bangladesh. India, Nepal and Bhutan, the foreign secretary said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
