<HEADLINE> Bank Director Arrested on Charge of Forgery in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Phnom Penh, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A director of a local bank
has been arrested on a warrant alleging forgery and embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
The English language newspaper, "Cambodia Daily", reported
that Heng Kim Y, director of Thaneakear Khmer (Khmer Bank), was
arrested last Thursday and was being held in prison. The paper was
quoting the deputy chief of the penal department of the Phnom Penh
Municipal Police.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sok, director general of the National Bank of Cambodia
(NBC) was quoted as saying that a warrant for Heng Kim Y's arrest
was issued by Municipal Court director, Un Sarith, and the NBC had
taken over administration of the Khmer Bank, which was closed for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily, Chea Sok said shareholders complained
that Heng Kim Y forged documents allowing him to pocket part of
the four million U.S. dollars that the bank was required to have in
reserve under Cambodian banking laws. But he did not specify the
amount the shareholders claimed Heng Kim Y had embezzled.
</P>
<P>
NBC officials were now auditing the books at Khmer Bank to find
out if there was any sign of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
The Khmer Bank opened its doors for business on September 27,
1996. It did not have a National Bank license, and the NBC had
threatened to close it on this account.
</P>
<P>
The daily said Heng Kim Y protested that he had deposited the
required four million dollars in capital at the central bank, but
NBC officials still refused to give him a license. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
