<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's President Arrives in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's President Robert
Mugabe arrived in Cyprus this afternoon for a three-day state
visit.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Larnaca Airport, President Mugabe said that
the peoples of Zimbabwe and Cyprus are great friends and allies.
</P>
<P>
He called on Turkey to withdraw its troops from the island
and "leave it to the people of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"They (the people of Cyprus) are mature and wise enough to
settle their own internal problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming Mugabe, Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides said
that the president of Zimbabwe has been "a great friend of
Cyprus, he has raised his voice for justice for Cyprus many
times."
</P>
<P>
President Clerides said that talks with his Zimbabwean
counterpart will serve to promote closer relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents are expected to hold talks later today at
the Presidential Palace here, which will focus on the Cyprus
problem, international issues of mutual concern and issues of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Mugabe will address a special session of
the House of Representatives and meet with House President
Spyros Kyprianou.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into two zones since 1974, when Turkey
sent troops to protect the Turkish Cyprus minority after a
short-lived Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
