<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bildt Opens Regional Office in Mostar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The International High
Representative for Bosnia, Carl Bildt, opened a United Nations
regional office today in Mostar to succeed the European Union (EU)
mission.
</P>
<P>
The new regional office will have wide authority in the
implementation of the Dayton accord throughout southern
Herzegovina, according to Croat radio in Mostar.
</P>
<P>
The office will be headed by the present EU Special Envoy,
Martin Garrod, who told Radio Sarajevo on New Year's eve that his
mission in Mostar over the past few months had been a political
failure.
</P>
<P>
Mostar, in the south of Bosnia, remains a divided city with
Muslim control in the east and Croats in the west.
</P>
<P>
Despite strong pressure from the international community, there
was still no freedom of movement between the two sectors, and no
single police force there to guarantee safety.
</P>
<P>
In the city, two administrative systems function separately.
Schools are separate, and so are health and financial systems.
</P>
<P>
According to Muslim Radio Sarajevo, instead of safe refugee
repatriation to their homes, Croats in Mostar had driven 74 Muslim
families out of their homes since the signing of the Dayton accord
in late 1995.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees reported Sunday in
Sarajevo the latest case of expulsion was carried out on Sunday by
Croat police, who expelled a pregnant Muslim woman from her
home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
