<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Army Promises not to Use Force Against Protesters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Belgrade student leaders said
Monday that Federal Yugoslav Army has promised not to intervene
against their anti-government protest to restore opposition
election victories annulled by President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made by the head of the army, Chief of General
Staff Gen. Momcilo Perisic on Monday at a meeting in Belgrade with
a five-member student delegation, the students said.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from an hour-long meeting held at the army
headquarters, the student leaders said they received further
assurance from Perisic that the Federal army wanted the political
disputes to be solved peacefully.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the General Staff's Information Service
confirmed the army position by saying that Perisic told the
students the current problems had to be overcome in the "legal
institutions" of the state, as in other democratic countries, in
order that Yugoslavia may be incorporated into the international
community as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
The opposition coalition Zajedno has been organizing massive
but peaceful demonstrations in Belgrade over the past seven weeks
to protest the annulment of the local elections in November by the
ruling Socialist Party of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Zajedno claims it had won the local elections in 14 out of 18
biggest cities and demands the reinstatement of the election
results and the recognition of their election victories.
</P>
<P>
But the government said last week that Zajedno had won in a few
of the smaller cities and insisted that in other districts no
party gained a majority or the results were inconclusive and
neeeded further study.
</P>
<P>
Zajedno was particularly concerned recently that the government
might use force to end the political crisis as it did in March
1991.
</P>
<P>
Zajedno leaders called for another protest march to the main
cathedral on Monday evening, the Christmas eve, to mark the
Orthodox Christmas. So far there is no immediate sign of a
peaceful settlement of the political crisis in Serbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
