<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Car Sales Down 5.5 Percent in November 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- New car registrations in the
European Union(EU) fell by 5.5 percent in November 1996, compared
with the same period in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This was reported by the twice-weekly news publication European
Report quoting the latest figures published by the European
Automobile Manufacturers' Association(ACEA).
</P>
<P>
It reported that the situation was broadly similar over the
seventeen European markets covered by ACEA figures(the 15 EU
member states plus Norway and Switzerland).
</P>
<P>
France suffered the sharpest decline(-21.8 percent), while
Ireland enjoyed the strongest growth(+83 percent). The Volkswagen
group remains the leading car maker with 17.9 percent of market
share.
</P>
<P>
Besides Ireland, new vehicle sales rose in eight countries in
November 1996, compared with the corresponding month in 1995:
notably in the Scandinavian countries, but also in Spain and
Portugal, and to a lesser extent the Netherlands and Greece.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, these figures could not hide the fact
that a majority of countries had recorded an average 5.5 percent
decline on November 1995. The downward trend is unequivocal in
Belgium and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Notwithstanding, EU car sales have risen 6.3 percent between
January and November 1996.
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen has consolidated its leading position with a 9.3
percent increase in sales over the first nine months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Japanese car sales have risen 6.8 percent, while South Korean
manufacturers now account for two percent of the market, with sales
up 38.8 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
