<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Africa to Harmonize Labor Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania are
scheduled to meet in Kampala next February to harmonize their
labor laws, the newspaper East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper said that the meeting in which the
representatives of the labor ministries of the three countries
will take part would serve as part of initial moves to make it
easier for east Africans to work in any of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the disbandment of the East African Community in
1977, citizens of the east African region could work without a
permit in any of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was proposed by Uganda during the the last East
African Commission meeting held on December 6.
</P>
<P>
At the commission meeting, the three countries also agreed to
harmonize their national legislations on refugees in regard to
employment, education, settlement and resettlement.
</P>
<P>
An information sharing system on asylum will be set up in
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania to promote uniform treatment of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted one delegate who will attend the meeting as
saying that "in order to strengthen our relationship we must have
free movement of people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
