<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Customs Revenue Up 46 Percent in 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nigeria Customs Service
recorded a revenue of some 69.3 billion Naira (about 866 million
U.S. Dollars) in the first 11 months of last year, an increase of
46 percent over the same year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
According to the government-owned New Nigerian newspaper
today, the general increase in all customs houses across the
country was attributed to the resolve of the customs management
to ensure its revenue collection machinery is strengthened in
furtherance of the economic interests of the country.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Sole Administrator of the Customs, S.O.G.
Ango as saying that 48.4 billion Naira, or nearly 70 percent, of
the total revenue was credited into the federation account, which
represented total collections from imports, excise and fees.
</P>
<P>
The remainings were collected by the customs on behalf of some
other government agencies, including the Nigerian Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
To sanitize the industry in an image-building effort, the
customs service has recently carried out some reorganization with
dismissals and disciplinary measures.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more than 20 senior customs officers have been
fired for official misconduct ranging from illegal clearance of
containers, undervaluation of imported goods to collusion with
unscrupulous importers and clearing agents in evading duty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
