<HEADLINE> Donors Blamed for Stopping Disbursement of Zanzibar Development Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma today blamed some donor countries for threatening
to stop disbursement of development funds earmarked for Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
He said although the Zanzibar government appreaciated aid,
donors should not use cheap excuses to embarrass it.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, Omar stated this when
opening a water well project at Kaburi Kikombe near the town of
Zanzibar as part of celebrations to mark the 33rd anniversary
of the Zanzibar January Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Zanzibar believe that Omar's remarks were in reaction
to the move by Finland to suspend development aid to Zanzibar's rural
water supply project.
</P>
<P>
Finland is reported to have pulled out of the multi-million
Shilling project because of the failure by the government to estblish
the water authority and introduce water service charges to meet
running costs and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
At present, Zanzibaris are supplied with water free of charge. The
government foots the bill.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Omar insisted that it was only through self help
projects that the people could solve problems facing them and at the
same time save the government from embarrassments against donor
countries.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the Zanzibar government for its efforts to solve water
problems for the people, saying it is encouraging the government
managed to accomplish the Kaburi Kikombe water project without
external support.
</P>
<P>
The Kaburi Kikombe water project can produce about 125 litres
of water per hour. It will serve about 100,000 residents in
Zanzibar Town.  enditem

