<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Computer Plans to Shrink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Apple Computer, one of the
leading computer makers of the world, will suffer greater losses
during the last quarter of 1996, according to a report of the USA
Today.
</P>
<P>
The company faces more cost cutting and possible layoffs after
announcing late Friday that it expects an operating loss of 100
million to 150 million the quarter ended December, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The company underwent a year of turmoil and restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The size of the loss indicates Apple has yet to get its
business plan in shape, and that many consumers are unconvinced
that it can survive long term.
</P>
<P>
Gilbert Amelio, who became Apple's chief executive officer in
February, said Apple will shrink more than he expected, to about 8
billion U.S. dollars in revenue this fiscal year. That would be
down 18 percent from last year's 9.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On December 20, Apple announced its 400 million U.S. dollar
purchase of NeXT Software, founded by Apple co-founder Steven
Jobs. Apple will use NeXT's technology to create a new operating
system, which controls the look and feel of computers.
</P>
<P>
Apple managed a 25 million U.S. dollar profit in the
July-September quarter after three quarterly losses, according to
the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Popularize Basic Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
expected to spend at least 720 million U.S. Dollars to improve
the education system in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government wants to restructure the education system so
every Zambian of school going age can attain the minimum of grade
nine education by the year 2015, according to a national policy
on education document obtained from the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
The government will rehabilitate existing infrastructure and
build new schools, especially in the peri-urban areas. The
exercise will be funded by donors, the government and the
community through cost-sharing.
</P>
<P>
"The first element of the approach will be to ensure that
every child can enter school at the appropriate age and receive
at least seven years of good quality education," said the
document which was signed by Education Minister Syamukayumbu
Syamujaye last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The second element will be to ensure that every pupil who
completes grade seven can enter grades eight and nine," according
to the document.
</P>
<P>
Communities will be expected to provide the infrastructure
while the government will provide technical advice, teachers,
equipment and materials for the exercise, the document said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Zambian education system, grades one to seven
are for lower basic education, grades eight to nine for middle
basic education and grades 10 to 11 for higher education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-06 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Extremists Sentenced to Death in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Five extremists from a militant
group were sentenced to death today and 19 others received prison
terms for the assassinations of eight police officers and several
civilians in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Higher State Security Court sentenced four members
of the out-lawed Assiut Organization to a 15-year imprisonment,
while nine others got ten years and a minor five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
Seven defendants were acquited in the case, while charges
against another were dropped because of his death.
</P>
<P>
Eight members of the tried were still at large, including two
of those sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
The court held its hearing this morning under unprecedented
high security measures in the presence of dozens of local and
foreign reporters.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three months, the court held 20 hearings and
listened to testimonies, made by 35 witnesses while there were 15
attorneys for the defense.
</P>
<P>
The militants were convicted of murdering seven policemen
including the assistant security director in the province of
Assiut.
</P>
<P>
They were also charged with acquisition of arms, ammunition and
explosives and forging official documents.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992 Muslim militants have staged a campaign of violence
to topple the Egyptian government. More than 1,000 people have
died in the violence, most of them policemen and civilians and
56 extremists have been hanged by the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
