<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infant Mortality Rate Goes up in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Infant mortality in Zimbabwe
rises from 52 per 1,000 in the 1980s to currently 77 per 1,000,
Hagar Mapondera, the Coordinator of Zimbabwe's Midwives Group,
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the maternal mortality rate has doubled from 100
per 100,000 to 200 per 100,000 live births, she said.
</P>
<P>
The increase is due to the high HIV (virus which can cause
the fatal AIDS disease) infections, said Mapondera.
</P>
<P>
However, "in other African countries, maternala mortality is as
high as 600 per 100,000 live births," she said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that one-tenth of more than 11 million
Zimbabweans have been infected with HIV and 300-to-500 people are
killed by AIDS-related diseases every week in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
