<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Insists on WTO's Arbitration of U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will not
withdraw its demand for an arbitration by the World Trade
Organization (WTO) on U.S. anti-Cuba Helms-Burton Act although
U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered a six-month suspension of the
act's implementation last Friday, Roderick Abbott, head of EU's
mission in Geneva, reaffirmed here today.
</P>
<P>
Roderick Abbott told reporters that Clinton's decision to delay
the implementation of the Helms-Burton Act does not mean that the
U.S. government will modify the act, under which foreign companies
doing business in Cuba would be sued by U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
On November 20, 1996, WTO decided to set up an independent
panel to examine the controversial U.S. Helms-Burton law enacted
last March. The panel is to report its findings in no more than
six months after its establishment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
