<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-06 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Officially Confirms Missile Deal with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
confirmed to have signed a deal to buy Russian-made S-300
surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides told a private television
network today that the deal "is a reality, the process has been
concluded and the relevant agreement signed."
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, pointed out the missiles can not be
delivered immediately, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The multi-million dollar arms deal, believed to have been
signed Saturday, has caused the United States, European Union
countries and Turkey to express grave concern over the military
build-up in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"Our ambassador to the U.S. was summoned to the State
Department where the American administration expressed its deep
concern about our moves," Michaelides told Antena TV.
</P>
<P>
A European country has taken similar stance about the deal, the
minister disclosed, but refrained from naming the specific country.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said Ankara has issued warning that the
deal will not help the peace process in Cyprus and threatened to
take "counter-measures."
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, a spokesman for the Russian Rosvoorouzhenie company
which signed the deal has said the deal is unlikely to upset the
military balance in the region, because they are defensive
military hardware.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides explained that this deal conveys the message that
efforts towards a settlement to the Cyprus issue must be
intensified and speeded up.
</P>
<P>
"The missiles will boost our defense capability and are not in
any way an act of aggression," he added, noting that President
Glafcos Clerides' proposal for the demilitarization of Cyprus is
still on the cards.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the new missiles, with a range
of 150 kilometers, will be deployed to protect naval and air
bases under construction on the west coast of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The bases are being built under a joint defense pact between
Cyprus and Greece, agreed in November 1993 to face possible
Turkish threats.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops
and seized the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
