<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-06 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Committed to Kuwaiti Security: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
continue to carry out its commitment to the security of Kuwait
mainly through its military presence both in the Gulf and Kuwait
in the new year, a senior American diplomat said here today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Kuwait Ryan Crocker said in an interview
with the Kuwait News Agency that "the U.S. commitment to the
security of Kuwait is absolutely unshakable, we have reaffirmed
this on numerous occasions and throughout President Bill
Clinton's term of office."
</P>
<P>
He said that "with respect to our military levels in Kuwait
which are the embodiment of that commitment, the numbers and the
composition of our forces will change according to operational
requirements and according to circumstances."
</P>
<P>
The United States currently has 25,000 military personnel in
the Gulf region, including Kuwait. It sent two aircraft carriers,
B-52 bombers, F-117a Stealth fighters and Patriot missiles to the
Gulf last September in its confrontation with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat said that "we have a number of very flexible
options to assure that at all times we have adequate forces in
the area to back-up our commitments that is the case now and
continues to be the case."
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Iraq remains the major threat to its
neighbors, saying "as we enter this new year and look back at
nearly the six years that have passed since the liberation of
Kuwait, the regime in Baghdad has demonstrated (this) time and
again."
</P>
<P>
The United States and Kuwait signed a military agreement
following the Gulf War under which the U.S. promised to defend
the small oil-rich Emirate against foreign attacks and frequent
military exercises were held between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Since last September, U.S. and Kuwait have been conducting a
series of joint military training maneuvers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
