<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb President Says No Haggling About Brcko </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb president Biljana
Plavsic said Monday that the town of Brcko was important for the
Republika Srpska and there could be no haggling about it.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no deals or sale regarding Brcko," a town in
northeastern Bosnia which links the northwestern and eastern parts
of the Republika Srpska, Plavsic told a political gathering in
Banja Luka, the Serb largest city in the northwest, Tanjug news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Both the Serbs and Muslims claim sovereignty over the
controversial town which is of strategic importance to both sides.
Under the Dayton agreement, the status of Brcko will be decided
under international arbitration by the end of 1996 but the
deadline was postponed till February 20 of this year.
</P>
<P>
In the same day, the Serb Vice-President Dragoljub Mirjanic
held a meeting with U.S. official Jim Coel in Banja Luka. He told
reporters after the meeting that the U.S. state department
representative had been informed about a decisive stand of the
Republika Srpska -- the Serbs would fight for ensuring that Brcko
remains part of the Serb territory.
</P>
<P>
Coel promised to inform the U.S. state department about talks
with Serb leaders so that the U.S. administration could take a
clear stand on all controversial issues regarding the
implementation of the Dayton agreement, Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Mirjanic and Coel raised the issue of the
exchange of prisoners of war and information about missing persons
between the Bosnian Serb, Croat and Muslim sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
