<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-06 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Concerned About Military Build-up in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkey expressed today grave
concern over the military build-up in Cyprus following the
signing of an arms deal of purchasing Russian-made missiles
between Russia and the island state.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Omer Akbel told reporters that
Turkey firmly opposed a change of the power balance on the
divided island.
</P>
<P>
He said the Turkish government would never allow any
endangerment of the Turkish Cypriots living in the northern part
of what he called the heavily militarized country.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Turkey would take necessary actions if the
situation on the island continued to deteriorate. However, he
did not elaborate on what actions Turkey might take.
</P>
<P>
"What we say to Russian authorities, first, is to remind them
of their special responsibilities as a U.N. Security Council
permanent member, secondly, not to change the balance on the
island," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Cypriot ministers and representatives of the
Russian state-controlled Rosvoorouzhenie company concluded a
multi-million-dollar surface-to-air missile contract at a meeting
on the eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides confirmed the arms
deal today. He told a private television network that the deal
"is a reality, the process has been conducted and the relevant
agreement signed."
</P>
<P>
The arms deal between Greek Cypriots and the Russians has
aroused strong opposition from both Turkish Cypriots and Turkey,
which is the only country in the world to recognize the
self-claimed "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas accused Moscow of
displaying enmity toward Turks by selling missiles to Greek
Cypriots, warning that Cyprus was now on the verge of an armed
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the NATO, are at odds over
the divided strategic island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into two parts since 1974 when the
Turkish troops landed on the island and took control of the
northern part following an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots
seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
