<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies Letter Bombs from Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today renewed its denial
that the letter bombs sent to Washington had been mailed from
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, political advisor to Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak told reporters, "There is no evidence as yet that the
letter bombs discovered at a Washington newspaper office and a
Kansas jail in the United States were sent from Egypt."
</P>
<P>
Eight letter bombs disguised as Christmas cards, carrying the
seal of Alexandria post, were dispatched separately to the
Washington bureau of the London-based Saudi newspaper Al Hayat's
and to a jail around Leavenworth, Kansas in the U.S. Friday.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting with the U.S. Ambassador Edward
Walker, he said it would be premature to jump to any conclusion
and that the agencies concerned are examining the issue very
accurately.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador also discredited reports about a visit by a team
of the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) to Egypt to probe the
possibility of the dispatch of letter bombs from Egypt to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Walker stressed that security agencies in both countries
maintain normal relations and "seek clarifications from each
other." No committee was set up to examine the matter, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is natural that the two sides discuss the topic
of letter bombs and try to resolve the case.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, security bodies here dismissed the possibility that
these bombs had slipped out of Egypt. They suggested that fake
stamps can be made on letters to confuse investigators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
