<HEADLINE> International Observers to Be Stationed in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Palestine decided
today to ask international observers to station in Hebron
following partial Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank
city.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators signed a protocol in Jericho this afternoon, according
to a state-run Israel Radio report.
</P>
<P>
It said that under the accord, an additional 180 observers from
Denmark, Italy, Sweden, Switzerland and Turkey will join the 30
Norwegian peace-keepers already stationed in Hebron. Invitations
are to be sent out immediately to the countries concerned.
</P>
<P>
The document, initialed by Israeli Foreign Ministry Director
General Eitan Bentsur and Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat, will be appended to the impending Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said that
the Hebron redeployment agreement has been wrapped up in writing
by both sides and that differences now focus on further Israeli
redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Appearing at the Knesset (Israeli parliament) Foreign Affairs
and Defense Committee, Mordechai said that under the security
arrangements, Israel will solely be responsible for safeguarding
the area of the Tomb of Patriarchs.
</P>
<P>
As to the Shuhada Street closed to the Palestinian citizens
for two years now, a solution has been found complete with a map,
Mordechai said, adding that American, Israeli and Palestinian
engineers have worked out a map to widen the street and install
sidewalk and lighting, so as to separate the Jewish settlers and
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai declared that shortly after the agreement is singed
the army can complete redeployment in Hebron in a very short
time.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Middle East peace coordinator Dennis Ross today continued
his efforts to narrow differences between the two sides. He met
with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu this morning and is
scheduled to have a meeting with Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat in the West Bank city of Bethlehem tonight.
</P>
<P>
Ross is reportedly trying to arrange another summit between
Netanyahu and Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
