<HEADLINE> UK Commercial Property Market Forecast to Boost in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- More industrial and commercial
companies in Britain are expecting to increase their property
holdings, according to a survey published Monday by the
Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by the CBI in conjunction with Grimley,
the international property advisers, showed that a net balance of
six percent of companies planned to increase property holdings in
the first half of this year, compared with three percent for the
previous six months.
</P>
<P>
The fifth biannual property survey, which covered 645 companies
in the country, found that big companies were more optimistic than
smaller ones of increasing output and hiring staff as well as
increasing office space.
</P>
<P>
The recovery in the commercial property market will be more
widespread, and the biggest increase is expected to come from
companies in the distribution, metal manufacturing, chemical
processing, transport and communication sector.
</P>
<P>
The strongest growth in demand for property is expected to be
in the northwest of England, Northern Ireland, greater London and
Scotland, but other parts of the southeast are likely to see a
downturn.
</P>
<P>
The main Reasons for capital spending on property are capacity
expansion, replacement and increasing efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"Companies are now noticeably more optimistic about employment
prospects than they were in previous surveys and that is now
feeding through into increased property demand," said Stuart
Morley, head of research at Grimley.

nnnn
03:40 03:40 g # NAB
</P>
</TEXT>
