<HEADLINE> Angolan Former Rebel Leader Invites Mandela to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 6 (Xinhua) --Angola's former rebel leader
Jonas Savimbi left here today for a visit to South Africa where
he will invite South African President Nelson Mandela to mediate
between him and Angolan President Eduard dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is believed to hold his fifth talks with President
Eduard dos Santos soon, the Angolan News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It is the third time for Mandela to meet Savimbi, the chairman
of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), said the report.
</P>
<P>
The main topic at the Savimbi-Mandela meeting would be the
difficulties facing Angola's peace process and the delays of the
solution to various problems facing the peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
One of the disputes between Savimbi and Santos is reportedly
the status of Savimbi in the future Angolan goverment. The
Angolan president once offered the position of Vice President to
Savimbi, but was refused.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has on many occasions expressed
its support for the peace process in Angola. Mandela has attended
the summit of the southern African leaders held in Launda in last
October at which peace in Angola was discussed.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has maintained regular telephone contacts with the
Angolan president. 
</P>
