<HEADLINE> Zanzibar To Introduce Cost-Sharing System into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar Health
Ministry is planning to introduce cost-sharing system into the
originally charge-free health services in the town of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Saleh Sadik Osman, the ministry's Principal Secretary, told
the Daily News newspaper in the town today that the plan has gone
to the government.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for the outcome of our proposal," Osman said.
</P>
<P>
If the plan gets approval and takes into effect, patients will
have to pay 100 Tanzania Shillings (about 16 U.S. cents) for
blood tests in the state-owned hospitals.
</P>
<P>
However, it will still be far lower than the similar charges
in private hospitals, which are currently between 150 and 300
Shillings (25 to 50 cents), said Osman.
</P>
<P>
He said that patients who can't afford the charges will
be exempted from paying for their health services.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibaris have enjoyed health service free of charge for
many years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
