<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Economy Picks up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said today the country's economy has picked up as
its exports are increasing faster than imports, which leads to a
improved trade balance.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa told foreign diplomatic corps that the inflation in the
country fell from November's 27 percent to currently 16 percent
due to the government's tightened fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
"Private investments are picking up, notably in the tourism and
mining sectors as well as manufacturing," he said.
</P>
<P>
All these achievements have been made by the continuing
restructuring of the economy, including divestiture and
pritivization, said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
The governmental policies implemented last year also boosted
the confidence of donors and investors in the country's
economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania hopes to negotiate with the Paris Club members on
debt relief by the end of this month so as to get continuous
understanding and support from the donors, Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
Debt relief will help the country achieve a stronger,
sustainable and self-reliant development, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the regional cooperation, Mkapa said since the inauguration
of the East African Cooperation Secretariat, comprising Tanzania,
Uganda and Kenya, in March, currencies of the three countries
are now convertible inside the region.
</P>
<P>
Financial aids are being sought for the East African digital
telecommunications project and for improving roads in the region,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time the three countries are taking steps to develop
East Africa as a single trade and investment area, as well as to
improve the navigational and environmental status of Lake Victoria,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa vowed to continue to make every efforts to promote East
African Cooperation and pledged to remain a firm and ardent
member of the Southern Africa Development Community (SADC),
</P>
</TEXT>
