<HEADLINE> Egypt Reports 32 Oil Finds in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt made 32 oil finds and signed
14 agreements for oil prospection with global companies last year,
Egyptian Minister of Oil Hamdy el-Banbi said today.
</P>
<P>
These companies are expected to spend some 300 million
U.S. dollars on drilling 83 wildcats over a total area of 142,000
square kilometers across the country, the oil minister said in a
report made before the People's Assembly's Industry and Energy
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Among the 32 oil finds, 12 produce oil while the remaining 20
give natural gas, Banbi added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's oil output amounts to 44 million tonnes and natural gas
production reaches 10.1 million tonnes, in comparison with the 32
million tonnes of overall output in 1983, the oil minister said.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas fields in the Nile Delta and on the Mediterranean
coast make up 60 percent of Egypt's total output while the
remaining comes from the Western Desert, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for crude oil, Delta and Mediterranean coast produce 50
percent, the Western Desert produces 33 percent and the Gulf of
Suez 17 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Local consumption of petroleum products has reached 16.5
million tonnes along with two million tonnes of natural gas, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has tried hard to boost the role of the private
sector in oil exploration and increasing the capacity of
refineries as well as encouraging gas-fueled industries, the oil
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
