<HEADLINE> Lebanese Speaker Rules out Achieving Peace With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berri today ruled out the possibility that Lebanon and Syria will
achieve peace with Israel in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, the Shiite house speaker
also ruled out a full-scale war with Israel, saying that "the
Israelis are going on a destructive war" in south Lebanon and
would not stop it.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe that the year 1997 will be a year of peace,
but it will be a year of pressure especially on Lebanon and
Syria," Berri told reporters in the Parliamentary Building.
</P>
<P>
"We should pay attention to this and should reassert our
national unity," said the house speaker, who is also the head of
the pro-Syrian Amal Movement.
</P>
<P>
"You should look at what is happening in south Lebanon, there
are daily fightings," he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned against creating fracture between the resistance
and the people and between the resistance and the government,
and causing fracture or separation between Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
On the fate of the peace negotiations on the Lebanese and
Syrian tracks, Berri noted that both Lebanon and Syria
participated in the peace talks on the basis of the October 1991
Madrid peace conference decisions and United Nations
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Syria and Israel were suspended last
February amid a spate of suicide bombings in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Berri emphasized Syria's demand to resume the peace talks
with the Jewish state from where they stopped without going back
to the zero point.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that when he met Hosni Mubarak in Cairo at the
weekend, the Egyptian president told him a secret that he had
been informed by former Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin a
readiness to give up the Golan Heights the Jewish state occupied
in 1967.
</P>
<P>
But the former Labor prime minister, who was shot dead by a
Jewish extremist at a peace rally in November 1995, had preferred
to wait and see what Syria would give in normalization in
exchange for the Israeli pullout, Berri quoted the Egyptian
president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Berri said that Lebanon is "a strong point rather than a weak
point" in the Middle East peace process as long as the Lebanese
uphold the national unity and internal solidarity.
</P>
<P>
"If (Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin) Netanyahu think that
Lebanon is a weak point, we tell him that we are a strong point,
and in our hands a lot of cards on condition that we continue to
uphold the national unity and the internal solidarity," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We will not be a weak point unless we are split and the
Lebanese track is separated from the Syrian track and a fracture
is created between the resistance and the state," the house
speaker said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
