<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Genes for Cassava in Nigeria Developed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Techniques for the transfer of
"foreign" genes into cassava in Nigeria and Colombia have been
developed, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The development would open up the possibilities of improving
cassava, one of the major food sources for Nigerians, in ways which
have hitherto eluded researchers, the report said,
quoting the "Spore", a bulletin of information for agricultural
development in African, Carribean and Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the bulletin, the breakthrough would make it possible
to regenerate cassava plantlets from single cells from which mature
cassava plants could be produced.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the University of Bath in England, achieved this with
two improved cultivars from Nigeria and Colombia, but the workability
of the new techniques with all cassava varieties has not yet been
established, it said.
</P>
<P>
Similar techniques have also been developed by scientists in the
United States and Switzerland, which should also make it possible to
introduce pest and disease resistance to improve the quality and
storing properties of the crops in some countries.
</P>
<P>
In another development, scientists in the nigeria-based
international institute of tropical agriculture have evaluated the
drought tolerance of about 900 different strains of cowpea together
with their Japanese colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The findings show that drought-tolerant strains yield about one ton
per hectare without irrigation during the dry season in tropical
Africa, good for areas in lack of rainfall.
</P>
<P>
Experiement carried out in north Nigeria's Kano State has proved
the good properties of the drough-tolerant strains, the bulletin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Takes Measures to Prevent Looming Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has taken urgent measures
to avert a looming fuel shortage caused by the recent damage of
Tanzania's Single Point Mooring (SPM) on off-loading oil from
ships, Energy Minister Suresh Desai said today.
</P>
<P>
Zambia imports most of its crude oil from Tanzanian ports.
Therefore, the SPM, gutted by fire during Christmas holidays, is
critical to the oil supplies to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
However, the SPM facility now is being repaired and
arrangements for using smaller crude oil off-loading facilities
instead have been made in case the repairing work continues
beyond 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's oil reserve can last for 60 days, said Desai.
</P>
<P>
Oil tanks may use the secured smaller crude oil off-loading
facility to get closer to the shore of the Dar Es Salaam port in
Tanzania, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SPM was damaged last September, resulting in a fuel crisis
in Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
