<HEADLINE> Job Chances for UK Graduates Forecast to Rise in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Job prospects for graduates in
Britain are the best since 1990 and vacancies will grow rapidly
this year, according to a survey published today by the
Association of Graduate Recruiters (AGR).
</P>
<P>
The annual survey of 260 leading companies found that vacancies
for graduates are increasing at a faster rate than student numbers
for the first time in five years.
</P>
<P>
The association said that the number of graduate jobs stayed
the same almost throughout the recession, but the number of
graduates coming out of the university system has doubled over the
past five years, so graduates had to battle hard for top jobs
during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
However, the AGR, which represents both private and public
employers, forecast an 11.5 percent growth in vacancies for
graduates this year, and said that employers will offer markedly
higher starting salaries in an effort to hire the best young
graduates.
</P>
<P>
The rush for the best graduates is partly caused by economic
growth and partly by the increasing impact of globalization, which
is driving companies to recruit more highly-educated staff than in
the past, said the AGR.
</P>
<P>
More than a third of companies said that they could not find
suitable graduates for scientific, engineering, technical,
research and development jobs, particularly those in computing.
</P>
<P>
Roly Cockman, chief executive of the association, said that the
AGR would like to see university courses deliver the skills
employers needed, which means more teamwork and project work and
less straightforward lecturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
