<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Government Apologizes to Mulroney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government
apologized today to former Prime Minister Brian Mulroney for
suggesting that he was involved in criminal activity in the Airbus
affair.
</P>
<P>
The government also agreed to pay the legal bills, somewhere
around 730,000 U.S. dollars, in Mulroney's libel suit against it.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Canada and the RCMP (Royal Canadian Mounted
Police) regret any damage suffered by Mr. Mulroney and his family
and fully apologize to them," said the settlement agreement, which
was made public this morning.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the language contained in the Request for Assistance
indicates, wrongly, that the RCMP had reached conclusion that Mr.
Mulroney had engaged in criminal activity," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the evidence received to date, the RCMP acknowledges
that any conclusions of wrongdoing by the former prime minister
were -- and are --unjustified," the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
The RCMP will pay to Mulroney all court fees, which will be
determined by an arbitrator. And Mulroney agrees to waive his
demand for damages.
</P>
<P>
Mulroney was suing the government for 36.5 million U.S. dollars
for alleging in a letter to Swiss authorities that he accepted as
much as 3.65 million dollars in kickbacks in the purchase of 34
Airbus planes in 1988 when he was the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The settlement, initiated by the government, was reached about
12 hours before the trial was to begin this morning in the Quebec
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement is in the best interests of the Canadian
government, the Canadian justice system and the Canadian
taxpayers," Justice Minister Allan Rock told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"The government's decision to resolve this case out-of-court is
good news," said RCMP Commissioner Philip Murray.
</P>
<P>
Having the civil case settled, the RCMP can focus its attention
on the criminal investigation of the Airbus affairs, Murray said,
adding "that probe is active and ongoing."
</P>
<P>
Mulroney also stressed that he has no objection to the RCMP
investigating him.
</P>
<P>
He launched the libel suit in November 1995 because the letter
sent by the Justice Department to the Swiss stated categorically
that he had accepted the kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
The letter sent in October 1995 requested assistance to search
bank accounts for evidence of the suspected payoffs.
</P>
<P>
Mulroney has also denied that he has any bank accounts in
Switzerland or anywhere else outside of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The RCMP first heard allegations in 1988 but dropped the case
for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
The case was reopened in 1995 after CBC-TV and Der Spiegel, a
German news magazine, suggested that Airbus may have paid 12.4
million dollars in kickbacks to Canadians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
