<HEADLINE> US Treasury Permits Food Export to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S Treasury has given
Cargill Inc., a Minneapolis firm, permission to export 500,000
tons of food to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea in a
barter transaction, an administration official said today.
</P>
<P>
The permission followed a statement issued by the DPRK a week
ago, which expressed "deep regret" over its submarine running
aground off South Korea's coast in last September.
</P>
<P>
A Cargill spokeswoman said the license to export the food to
the DPRK had been approved on December 30 in response to an
application submitted by Cargill, the world's largest private
grain company, to sell the DPRK up to 2 million tons of grain.
</P>
<P>
"We have received a license to export up to 500,000 tons of
good, consisting of wheat and/or rice," spokeswoman Laurie
Johnson said. "We probably will not have much more to say about
this, as a courtesy to the customer."
</P>
<P>
Reports said that U.S. experts this week will resume encasing
the DPRK's 8,000 spent nuclear fuel rods in steel and concrete for
safe storage before moving them out of the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Canning of the fuel rods was part of the nuclear agreement
between the United States and the DPRK, in which a U.S.-sponsored
Western consortium would provide funds for the replacement of two
Graphite reactors with light-water ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
