<HEADLINE> S.Africa's Mining Company Complets First Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's mining giant
Anglo American Corporation today announced that its Sadiola Hill Gold
Mine in west African nation, Mali, completed its first gold pour on
December 20 last year.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Johannesburg, the Corporation said the
pour signified the successful hot commissioning of the first
processing line, which was scheduled to reach full design capacity by
the end of February.
</P>
<P>
However, both modules of the plant are due to operate at full
output by the end of May this year, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The commissioning of the first module of the Sadiola Gold Plant
started in early November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The plant, at its full capacity, would produce approximately one
ton of gold a month, with the available oxide ore reserves containing
140 tons of gold.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American Corporation and Canada's Iamgold each owns a 38
percent stake in the Sadiola project, the Malian government owns 18
percent and the rest six percent is owned by the International
Finance Corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
