<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Sets Transport Master Plan for 1997-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Links between three key economic
zones and trans-Vietnam land, rail and water routes will take
priority in Vietnam's transport master plan for 1997-2000, it was
announced a here today.
</P>
<P>
Acting Minister of Transport and Communications Le Ngoc Hoan
said Vietnam had worked out an overall plan for transport and
communications development in the period between 1997 to 2000. Top
priority would be given to links between the economic areas as
well as major airports and sea ports of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
He said in the north, transport facilities would be built and
upgraded to help quickly develop the Hanoi-Haiphong-Quang Ninh
economic triangle. In the south, all efforts would be made to
build infrastructure for the Ho Chi Minh city-Dong Nai-Vung Ttau
economic zone.
</P>
<P>
In the central economic zone, the capacity of Da Nang port
would be expanded, and a road network constructed to link up Dung
Quat port, a new deep water port in central Vietnam, Hoan said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam would finish upgrading the whole 2,000 kilometers,
north-south backbone highway by the turn of this century, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hoan said that Vietnam was considering building a trans-nation
expressway linking Noi Bai international airport in Hanoi with Ha
Long in Quang Ninh province and Ho Chi Minh city, Long Thanh and
Vung Tau in southern Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Hoan said the ministry had adopted concrete measures in
collaboration with Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh city and other major cities
to tackle urban traffic problems by building more city-belt roads
with more overpasses.
</P>
<P>
Apart from state allocations and foreign investment and loans,
traffic charges in Vietnam would be increased to create another
financial source to meet the growing demands for development of
transport and communications facilities, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
