<HEADLINE> Yemen-Eritrea Dispute Over Hanish Islands Submits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- An arbitration court agreed
by Yemen and Eritrea will hold its first meeting in London next
week on how to resolve their dispute over the Hanish Islands, a
report reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
There had occurred a serious confrontation between Yemen and
Eritrea which both claimed their sovereignty over the small, arid
Hanish Islands on busy oil tanker routes not very far from the
outlet of the Red Sea and sent their troops there.
</P>
<P>
Fighting involving warships and aircraft broke out last year,
and each side accused the other of intruding into its territories
where potential oil deposit may abound.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the two countries signed an accord in October, 1996
in Paris to set up an arbitration court in London.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Yemen appointed an Egyptian and an
American to the court while Eritrea named an American and a
Briton. The fifth person, whose nationality has not been
identified, will head the court.
</P>
<P>
The dispute led to clashes in which at least 12 people were
killed last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
