<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Manufacturing Registers Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's key manufacturing
sector, which had depressed for most of 1995 due to lack of
demand, recovered last year to register an estimated four percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
The sector, which contributes about 25 percent of the
country's annual GDP, benefited from increased output in the
agro-based industries, whose performance was boosted by the
record agricultural harvest in the 1995/96 season.
</P>
<P>
Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries Chief Executive Joe
Foroma today said, "the first half of 1996 was a particularly
difficult period, with a combination of high inflation and
interest rates, as well as depressed local demand contributing to
sluggish performance."
</P>
<P>
"But the second half was better and as a result of that, I
believe we are going to have overall positive growth rate of
about four percent for the whole of 1996," Foroma said.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, the estimated growth level was "not good
enough" because of unused production capacity in many companies.
</P>
<P>
Foroma said his confederation believed there is potential for
more investment in Zimbabwe to create jobs and support efforts to
industrialize the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
