<HEADLINE> SAARC Meeting on TB Control Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A South Asian regional meeting
on tuberculosis (TB) opened here today with the aim to formulate a
new strategy for the treatment of the disease in the region, where
about 40 percent of the total TB patients in the world live.
</P>
<P>
The sixth meeting of the governing board of the SAARC
Tuberculosis Center is being attended by TB experts from SAARC
member countries.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting, the TB experts will exchange
information on the new development of TB treatment and hold
extensive discussions on how to propagate the thinking that the TB
disease is curable, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's meeting, Nepali Health Minister Arjun
Narsingh K.C. disclosed that the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Tuberculosis Center is to formulate a new program to promote TB
treatment in the region.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are about 300,000 TB patients in
South Asia and about 16,000 people die of the disease every year
in the region.
</P>
<P>
A seminar on pilot demonstration areas of TB control in SAARC
member countries will also be held, according to the organizers.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
