<HEADLINE> Philippine Beer Giant to Float More Commercial Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- San Miguel Corp., the largest
beer producer in the Philippines, will float 550 million pesos (21
million U.S. dollars) long-term commercial papers (LTCP) in 1997,
the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The five-year securities are the second part of a series of up
to 3 billion pesos (115 million dollars) LTCPs that the country's
Securities and Exchange Commission permits San Miguel to issue.
</P>
<P>
All Asia Capital and Trust Corp., the country's leading
financial institution, has arranged the floatation.
</P>
<P>
The publicly-listed San Miguel, which controls about 80 percent
of the domestic beer market shares, began to issue long-term bonds
in 1996 as part of its efforts to finance its modernization
program.
</P>
<P>
San Miguel Corp. has been in a bitter competition with its
rival Asia Brewery, which has gained a 20-percent share of the
domestic market since the late 1980s.  
