<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Liaoning Cancels Arbitrary Fees for Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province today canceled 118 kinds of fees worth a total of more
than 300 million yuan (about 3.6 billion US dollars) charged to
overseas investors, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the latest moves by the Chinese province to
improve its investment environment, vice-governor Gao Guozhu said
this afternoon at a press conference on eliminating arbitrary fees
for overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
To date, Liaoning has approved the establishment of over 14,600
overseas-funded enterprises, with contractual foreign investment
exceeding 20 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning launched a massive check on the collection of fees for
overseas-funded enterprises between April-August last year and
discovered many problems, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 units were involved in randomly collecting fees from
overseas-funded enterprise, Gao added.
</P>
<P>
"The provincial government has realized that arbitrary fees have
tarnished Liaoning's image and will damper investor interest in
our province," the vice-governor said.
</P>
<P>
"We're determined to wipe out all unreasonable and illegal fees
for overseas investors," Gao told the conference, which was
attended by consuls general from Japan, Germany, France, the
United States, Russia, the Republic of Korea, Switzerland and
Holland, as well as by representatives of some big overseas
companies.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Japanese consulate told Xinhua that he is
"very pleased that the Liaoning provincial government has taken a
resolute measure to eliminate arbitrary fees. It's something good
for overseas investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
