<HEADLINE> Social Sciences Research Booming In 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences -- often regarded as a think tank for
the Chinese government -- said here today that research conducted
by the country's scholars in the social sciences last year will
add to the development of the economy and society.
</P>
<P>
In particular, scholarly attention has been focused on
economics, said the spokesman for CASS, the top research
institute of social sciences and liberal arts in the country.
</P>
<P>
Research projects have been completed covering a range of
subjects, such as methods for coordinating the development of the
urban and rural economy, and determining the ways out for some of
China's state-enterprises that are in the red. Some of their
reports, such as "China's Industrial Development in 1996," have
been noticed by foreign institutes in Beijing, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other important findings are related to the reforms of
taxation, finance, and housing systems as well as the industrial
decision-making process, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
"Many of our suggestions have been adopted by government
departments," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "the scholars' work is playing a big role in
China's democratic and legal construction."
</P>
<P>
The academy has finished research on intellectual property
rights, human rights, and the history of the legal system of the
People's Republic of China. Many researchers took part in drafting
and revising key laws last year, including the "Criminal Law," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
They have also made their own forecasts regarding the country's
social situations, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Literature, philosophy and history were dynamic sectors,
despite a shortage of funding for academic studies.
</P>
<P>
And some lengthy books, including "The History of Chinese
Literature," are being compiled. Scholars still value the study of
Marxist philosophy, but are stepping up the research of Chinese
language, ancient history, the moral questions in the
ever-changing contemporary society, and the relationship between
culture and a market economy, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
China also boasts smaller academies of social sciences at
provincial and city levels, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
