<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Budget Surplus Drops in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government posted
a budgetary surplus of 6.8 billion pesos (26 million U.S. dollars)
as of October 1996, a sharp drop from the nearly 10 billion pesos
(38 million dollars) recorded a year ago, the Finance Department
said today.
</P>
<P>
This is the third consecutive year for the government to enjoy
a fiscal surplus. In 1994, the cash-starved government obtained
its first budgetary surplus of more than 15 billion pesos (57.3
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In its year-end report, the department said the government also
registered a surplus of 14.5 billion pesos (55.3 million dollars)
from the consolidated public sector financial position in the
first half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The strong performance of the fiscal sector was a major
contributory factor in the economic stability that the country is
currently enjoying," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said the interest rate of the 91-day treasury bills is at a
low level of 11.5 percent as of September, while inflation is at a
downtrend of 4.5 percent as of November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The total revenues earned by the government reached 341.4
billion pesos (13 billion dollars) as of October 1996, an increase
of 12.9 percent over the 302.5 billion pesos (11.5 billion
dollars) generated a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
To further improve its financial position, the government will
continue to push for more tax reform measures and the continuation
of the economic liberalization and deregulation efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
