<HEADLINE> 1,500 Zambians Arrested for Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,529 Zambians were
arrested locally and another 22 in foreign countries for
trafficking narcotic drugs in the year 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to information obtained today from the Drug
Enforcement Commission of Zambia, the drugs so far seized in the
country were eight tons of dagga (cannabis), 3,172 tablets of
valium, 5,600 mandrax tablets, 16 kilograms of opium and 4.5
kilograms of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
A Zambian drug trafficker arrested in South Africa has hit a
record in the southern African region who had carried seven
kilograms of cocaine with a street value of 3,000 million Kwacha
(2.4 million U.S. Dollars) tied to her body.
</P>
<P>
The rate of drug trafficking is on the increase. "Drug-abuse,
addiction and trafficking reached pandemic levels in 1996 in a
country fatally afflicted by other devastating problems like
HIV/AIDS and malaria," Southern Province Permanent Secretary
Sylvester Mpishi once said.
</P>
<P>
The Drug Enforcement Commission has intensified its action
against drug trafficking and drug abuse. Its offices in various
parts of the country are working clock round to deal with any
cases that may arise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
