<HEADLINE> EU, Canada Progress Towards Customs Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Canada planned to conclude their negotiations on a bilateral
agreement on customs cooperation early this year, a European
Commission spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
This was agreed on Monday during a meeting between EU
Customs and Taxation Commissioner, Mario Monti, and the Canadian
Minister of National Revenue, Mrs Jane Stewart.
</P>
<P>
"Commissioner Monti and Minister Stewart agreed that
negotiations on a bilateral agreement on customs cooperation and
mutual assistance should be pursued vigorously with the aim of
concluding them early in 1997," the spokesman for the European
Commission (EC), the executive body of the EU, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement will contribute to trade facilitation as well
as to the improved fight against fraud in the field of customs,"
the EC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The EC called the meeting the "first step" in following up
important aspects of the EU-Canada Action Plan, which was formally
adopted on December 17, 1996 at the EU-Canada Summit in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
The Action Plan calls for closer cooperation in the fields of
customs, indirect taxation and the fight against international crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
