<HEADLINE> S. Africa's New Antarctic Base to be Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A new South Africa
National Antarctic Base, which costs about 38 million Rands (8
million U.S. Dollars), will be put into operation soon, officials
said in Cape Town today.
</P>
<P>
Dirk Van Schalkwyk, South African director to Antarctic
Islands, told reporters on the SA Agulhas, a research and supply
ship that whether the Antarctic base will be open on January 18
or 19 should depend on the weather.
</P>
<P>
African National Congress (ANC) Senator Stefan Grove, who is
wheel chair-bound, will attend the opening ceremony, Van
Schalkwyk said, adding that the base has facilities for the
disabled in accordance with the new constitution.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's new Antarctic base, which was solidly built on
a rocky outcrop, is more permanent and cost-effective than the
old one, which was evacuated three years ago, said Environmental
Affairs and Tourism Deputy Director-General Francois Hanekom.
</P>
<P>
The SA Agulhas, carrying scientists, scientific equipment and
daily necessities of life, left for Antarctica today. Six
scientists and a woman doctor will stay at the base for 14
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
