<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan People's Party Announces Manifesto for Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 7 (Xinhua) -- In its manifesto announced
here today, Pakistan People's Party (PPP), led by deposed prime
minister Benazir Bhutto, vowed to repeal the 8th amendment to the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the manifesto at a press conference, Bhutto said
that her party prefers a four-year term for president, prime
minister and members of the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"However, the term for senators will be five years," she added.
</P>
<P>
So far, the terms of office for president, prime minister and
members of the National Assembly are five years.
</P>
<P>
Benazir Bhutto, who had come to power again in October 1993,
was sacked on November 5, 1996, by President Farooq Leghari who
exercised the power of the 8th amendment which authorizes the
president to dismiss a government when it cannot lead a country
properly.
</P>
<P>
Fresh elections are scheduled for February 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
The PPP's major legislative agenda for 1997-2002 includes an
increase in the number of national and provincial assembly seats,
a census under the supervision of the Judiciary and provision of
certain percentage of seats in the national and provincial
assemblies on proportional representation basis.
</P>
<P>
The economic agenda focuses on reducing tax levels in the 1997
budget to encourage more people to pay taxes. Tax revenues will be
increased by vigorous pursuit of tax evaders and search for
undeclared assets abroad.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto calls for maintaining a stable macro-economic
framework by keeping a low budget deficit, a prudent expansion in
money supply, equilibrium in balance of payments and stability in
prices.
</P>
<P>
The education agenda stresses the need to make basic education
universal and achieve 85 percent literacy by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The defense agenda calls for full support for the modernization
of the armed services to provide effective defense against outside
aggression.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
