<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Tens of thousands of striking South Korean workers Monday
began an arms wrestling with the government of Seoul to protest the
new labor law, which aims to ban pluralism of trade unions,
authorize massive lay-offs and sack striking workers. This is the
largest labor movement in South Korea since President Kim Young-Sam
came to power in early 1993.
</P>
<P>
-- The Belgian Minister of Justice Stefaan de Clerk has
complained about the lack of transparency and communication from his
French counterpart, Jacques Toubon, over a case of corruption in
Belgium, which involves the French Dassault-Aviation group and a
number of Belgian politicians. Serge Dassault, the boss of the
Dassault group and the mayor of the ruling PRP party of Corbeil,
south of Paris, is suspected to have offered kick-backs to Belgian
politicians to obtain contracts.
</P>
<P>
-- The French presidential office has denied a story told by
journalist Georges-Marc Benamou in his new book ``le Dernier
Mitterrand,'' in which the author said that President Francois
Mitterrand sent a personal envoy to Jacques Chirac on November 1,
1994, asking the latter to rapidly announce his candidature for the
1995 presidential election. Chirac did so three days later in the
northern city of Lille, the town of General Charles de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French state railway company SNCF has already lost 10
million francs (2 million U.S. dollars) because of the bad weather
which has been plaguing France since Christmas. About 10,000 to
30,000 SNCF travelers have been affected by weather-caused
incidents and 6,000 completely stranded on trains. The SNCF has to
refund tickets by 100 percent if the trains do not arrive on
schedule beyond three hours.
</P>
<P>
-- An investigation team of the European Parliament on bovine
spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), or mad cow disease, said in a
latest report that both British government and European agricultural
commissioners serving from 1989 to 1994 are responsible for the
spread of the BSE. London was accused of covering up some facts over
the BSE, while the commissioners are blamed for neglecting sanitary
controls of beef products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
