<HEADLINE> Philippines to Import Thousands of Tons of Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is considering
importing 300,000 to 500,000 metric tons of rice this year,
Agriculture Secretary Salvador Escudero said here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the projection was based on the fact that the
production of unhusked rice in 1996 dropped to 11.3 million metric
tons.
</P>
<P>
Escudero, however, stressed that this year's import is being
carefully studied and that no recommendation for rice import has
yet been presented to the Presidential Palace for approval.
</P>
<P>
He admitted however that there is a need for such import. "But
as to when the rice import will come in, that we don't know yet."
</P>
<P>
Agriculture registered a good performance last year, with an
annual growth rate of 6.6 percent. Although as a result, the rice
situation was much better than in 1995, the country still has to
import the needed amount, he said.
</P>
<P>
National food authorities said the Department of Agriculture
should be serious about when the import of rice should start,
adding that it is better to import it within the third quarter to
prevent any rice shortage like the one brought about by typhoons
in 1995.  
</P>
