<HEADLINE> Philippines to Continue Privatization Plan Until 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
continue to privatize state-owned assets until 1999 as part of its
efforts to generate revenues, a senior finance official said
today.
</P>
<P>
Crisanta Legaspi, director of the Committee on Privatization,
said that the body has privatized about 400 companies across the
country, or completed 80 percent of its privatization task.
</P>
<P>
She said some 100 more companies are scheduled to be privatized
before the committee ceases to function in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
Legapsi said that the government expects to generate at least
10 billion pesos (382 million U.S. dollars) this year from the
sales of government properties.
</P>
<P>
The government has raised some 44 billion pesos (1.7 billion
dollars) in revenues through selling off state assets in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
State assets falling under the privatization program include
government-controlled corporations, government-transferred assets,
sequestered properties being handled by the Presidential
Commission on Good Government.
</P>
<P>
In the coming three years, the privatization committee will
focus on the privatization of power and water projects, and social
services in areas of education, health and pension, Legapsi said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
