<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Management of Radio Frequency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- China will strengthen the
management over radio services throughout the country in a move to
safeguard state security and promote economic development, vice
premier Zou Jiahua said today at a conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Zou said at the working meeting of the State Radio Management
Committee that while the world has entered the information era,
the widespread use of radio technology has complicated China's
radio management and created problems.
</P>
<P>
It is important to protect limited radio frequency resources,
which are owned by the state, said Zou, who is also director of
the committee.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to research the technologies used for radio
frequency and to keep opening new channels, but at the same time
it is a must to adopt administrative, legal, technological and
economic means to manage and make use of frequency resources."
</P>
<P>
By 2000, China will set up a nationwide radio frequency
management computer network and a nationwide radio monitoring
system, Zou said.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jichuan, minister of posts and telecommunications and vice
director of the committee, said at the conference that radio
telecommunications have provided important information services to
people, thereby promoting the development of society.
</P>
<P>
By last November, China had set up nearly nine million radio
stations of various kinds, reaching 6.61 million
listeners. Meanwhile, the country reported 40 million pager users,
ranking first in the world.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged various radio management departments to
supervise paging stations as well as the production and sales of
radio signals transmission equipment, and to severely punish the
unauthorized set-up and use of radio stations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
