<HEADLINE> Pakistan People's Party Announces Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Benazir Bhutto, the deposed
Pakistani prime minister and leader of the Pakistan People's Party
(PPP), said here today that the foreign policy of her party is
Muslim and Asian in character.
</P>
<P>
"Our friendship with China remains the cornerstone of our
foreign policy," Bhutto said, announcing the PPP manifesto for the
upcoming general elections at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Bhutto told the press conference that the People's government
of Pakistan will counter anti-Islamic propaganda and make Pakistan
the model of an enlightened, modern, progressive and moderate
Islamic society.
</P>
<P>
The PPP manifesto said, "Being Asian we will be reaching out in
particular to the Gulf and Central and East Asia."
</P>
<P>
"The growing tension in the Muslim world requires us to help
our friends without taking sides," it said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan should base its relations with Afghanistan and the
Central Asian republics on strong economic ties and on the
principle of non-interference, it added.
</P>
<P>
"Iran remains of strategic importance to Pakistan," it noted,
adding, "Pakistan must establish strong political and economical
ties with South Africa and other fast-developing African States."
</P>
<P>
"In setting foreign policy and objective, we must remember that
the Cold War is over and that Pakistan must establish its own
identity and stand on its own feet," Bhutto said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan must also rely on better economic ties with other
countries as a long-term basis of developing relations with them,
she added.
</P>
<P>
Bhutto's government was dissolved by Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari on November 5, 1996, on charges of mismanagement and
rampant corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Pakistan Muslim League (Nawaz group),
which has the greatest potential to win the polls scheduled for
February 3, also stressed the need to consolidate and further the
friendship between Pakistan and China in its manifesto for the
elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
