<HEADLINE> Death Rate Remains High on Kenyan Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The death rate on Kenyan roads
is among the highest in the world, and it stands at 7.7 per 1,000
vehicles, much higher than South Africa with a death rate of 1.9
per 1,000 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's road death rate is alarmingly high, towering over
those of Britain and the United States, which have death rates of
0.2 per 1,000 vehicles, a report compiled by the International
Road Federation revealed.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, about one accident in five is fatal while one in 45
in Canada, said the report, adding that Kenya's roads are among
the most dangerous in the world.
</P>
<P>
Recent estimates show that Kenya has the higher number of road
accidents among developing countries with an average of 8.2 lives
lost daily.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Economic Affairs, a local civic
non-governmental organization, disclosed recently in a report
that Kenya loses about 73 million U.S. Dollars annually in
material damage, and more than 100 million Dollars in manpower as
a result of accidents on local roads.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, 10,308 accidents occurred on Kenyan roads, claiming
1,856 lives, and three years later the number of accidents rose
to 12,355 in which 2,516 people died in the east African country
which has only around 325,000 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the trend of higher road death rate in
the country has caused its economy dearly.
</P>
<P>
The high death rate is attributed to the crowded public
transport, ill-kept roads, ancient vehicles and poor medical
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Restarts in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of Sierra Leone's
rebel movement, the Revolutionary United Front (RUF), has arrived
in capital Freetown for peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
This would be the second round of peace talks following the
first one held 18 days ago.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said the current round of talks to begin by
Wednesday will be centered on the demobilization and encampment
of RUF combatants which should have commenced in December.
</P>
<P>
In fact, RUF spokesmen Fayia Musa and Ibrahim Jalloh had
already held informal closed-door talks late on Monday with
government representatives at the headquarters of the peace
commission in Freetown after their arrival that day.
</P>
<P>
Sheka Mansaray, national security adviser to President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah, said, "the talks are moving but at a painfully slow
pace."
</P>
<P>
"We are still waiting for the international community to
respond to our appeal to provide troops to monitor the
implementation of the peace process," said Mansaray.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the government has asked the RUF to form
itself into a political movement or party to keep in line with
the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"But this cannot be done overnight as certain conditions such
as the establishment of a trust fund for the RUF have to be met,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The cease-firetion accord signed in Abidjan stated that the RUF
shall begin to function as a political movement with "the rights,
privileges and duties provided by law immediately after the
signing of the peace agreement."
</P>
<P>
The agreement further provided that necessary conditions shall
be created to enable the RUF to register as a political movement
within 30 days of the implementation of the peace accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
