<HEADLINE> India May Fail to Meet Industrial Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government's hopes
of achieving a 12-percent industrial growth in fiscal 1996-97
appear to be a distant dream if recent trends are anything to go
by, the National Herald said today.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the continuous downtrend in industrial
production during the first nine months of April-December of
fiscal 1996, experts here feel that industrial growth will likely
slow down to 8 percent, as against an official target of 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, industry registered a
9.08-percent growth in the first six months of April-September in
fiscal 1996 over the same period in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Following the same trend, the growth dropped to below 7 percent
during November-December 1996 when industry was expected to
perform better in the second half of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Provisional estimates showed that during the two months of
November and December, growth in core sectors including steel,
cement, coal, power and petroleum declined further.
</P>
<P>
The broad industrial sectors which also include fertilizers,
crude oil, sugar, jute and ferro-alloys recorded deceleration in
growth rates over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, the government seems quite upbeat about achieving
a higher industrial growth. Industry Secretary N. Monhanty
recently said industrial growth in this fiscal year would pass the
10-percent mark. Finance Minister P. Chidambaram said in November
that "Industry is likely to touch previous year's growth of 12
percent."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
