<HEADLINE> China's Eximbank Named Best Samurai Bond Issuer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of China
(Eximbank) has been named the best issuer of Samurai bonds for the
year 1996 by the International Financing Review, a London-based
financial magazine.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese bank was selected for the honor out of more than
140 Samurai bond issuers in Japan last year, following its
successful floating of 20 billion yen (about 180 million US
dollars) in five-year Samurai bonds in Tokyo last August.
</P>
<P>
The bond issue, the first by the Eximbank in Japan, prospered
because it was rationally priced, well designed and attracted a
broad mix of investors, the IFR said.
</P>
<P>
The Eximbank is one of China's three policy-oriented banks
established in 1994 to finance the country's exports of machinery,
electronics and complete sets of equipment. It was given an AA-
rating for bond issues in Japan in early 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
