<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Economy to Grow Moderately in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Macao's economy is expected to
grow moderately in 1997 following a less than one percent growth
rate in 1996, according to economists.
</P>
<P>
According to an article in the Hong Kong and Macao Economic
Quarterly magazine published by the Bank of China, Macao's
economic growth in 1997 will be better than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The forecast is based on several factors in the new year: a 4.1
 percent growth of the world economy on average, a 10.5 percent
economic growth rate in China's mainland, Hong Kong's return to
the embrace of the motherland and Macao's growth of consumption.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's return to the embrace of the motherland is foreseen
as a major encouraging factor for Macao, serving both as a model
for Macao's return and bringing prosperity to such industries as
tourism, hotels and retails.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of the domestic national product -- the value
of goods and services produced -- is estimated at less than one
percent in 1996, mainly because of decreased investment and
consumption and a declining external trade. The inflation rate in
1996 is expected to reach five percent, 3.6 percent lower from in
the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
