<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Sugar Industry Still in Dire Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's ailing sugar
industry, which has been caught in a deep crisis since early last
year, is still facing enormous problems precipitated by a shortage
of raw material and an increase in production costs.
</P>
<P>
Sugar price remains at the center of the crisis. A price war
started early last year when sugarcane growers in Punjab and North
West Frontier province demanded exorbitantly high prices for their
raw material.
</P>
<P>
And the situation took a turn for worse when the government
increased the prices of electricity and gas in the last quarter of
1996, thus pushing sugar mills' cost of production to a new high.
</P>
<P>
Sugar mill owners are facing a difficult situation where they
seem to have no choice but to go out of business as they cannot
increase the price of sugar to match the increased cost of
production.
</P>
<P>
To avert a possible backlash, the government is pumping huge
quantities of imported sugar into the local market to keep the
price situation under control.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan imported more than 700,000 tons of sugar last year to
meet its domestic demand. The government has decided to import
another 50,000 tons to avoid sugar shortage during the forthcoming
holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the sugar industry noted that Pakistan's sugar
production in 1995-96 fiscal year was only about 2.4 million tons,
registering a 12.5 percent decline from the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The decline in sugar production is mainly caused by a shortage
of sugarcane. The harvest of sugarcane, the basic raw material for
sugar production, was largely affected by rain, floods and cloudy
weather.
</P>
<P>
Because of the severe shortage of sugarcane, four sugar mills
have already been forced out of business, and many of the sugar
mills in the country are running far below their capacity.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to expectations, the row over the prices of sugarcane
intensified this year and sugar mills have to delay the crushing
season by 30 days to reduce the pressure on the supply of raw
material.
</P>
<P>
However, the move did not produce the desired results and
growers continued to demand higher prices, triggering a cut-throat
competition between mill owners for the limited supply of
sugarcane.
</P>
<P>
With an expected five percent increase in sugar production
worldwide, there are almost no chances for Pakistan to export the
commodity.
</P>
<P>
As far as prices of sugarcane is concerned, there seems to be
no easy way out as neither the government nor the Sugar Mills
Associations (SMA) can force growers to sell sugarcane at a price
acceptable to the industry.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the sugar industry believe that the present
situation facing the industry is not only the short supply of raw
material, but also the poor quality of sugarcane which has far
less sucrose content than that of other sugar producing countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Agricultural Research Council has been working on
new seeds during the last few years to produce better quality
sugarcane. However, no major breakthrough has been achieved so
far.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is among those countries where per hectare yield of
sugarcane is very low. Despite millions of rupees spent on
research every year, the per hectare yield has not gone above 47
tons.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by SMA show that Pakistan's sugarcane
production in the last fiscal year went down to 45.23 million tons
from 47.17 million tons in the previous year. The supply of
sugarcane to sugar mills has already gone down to 60 percent from
80 percent a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
As nothing has so far happened to suggest that the present
situation prevailing in the sugar industry will be any better, it
is believed that Pakistan will have to continue its sugar import
to meet the domestic demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Howe Warns Hong Kong Against Trying to Transform China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Former British Foreign
Secretary Lord Geoffrey Howe said today that Hong Kong should not
be expected to be a bridgehead to trigger political change on the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon here today, Lord Howe said: "Hong Kong is
not entitled to regard itself, and they're unwise to regard itself
as a bridgehead of revolutionary change in the rest of the country
(China)."
</P>
<P>
"'One Country, two systems' is, what all we expected to be, a
two-way deal," said Howe, who was Britain's chief negotiator of
the Sino-British Joint Declaration on Hong Kong signed in 1984.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Declaration stipulates that Britain will return Hong
Kong to China on June 30, 1997, and China will in return grant a
high degree of autonomy to Hong Kong people in accordance with the
principle of "one country, two systems". Capitalism will continue
to prevail in Hong Kong and socialism will continue on the Chinese
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Saying that Hong Kong is entitled to its traditional way of
life, without interference from the mainland, Howe stressed: "The
proposition should work in the opposite direction as well,"
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong cannot and should not expect to transform China, and
trying to do so will risk Hong Kong itself," he warned.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the democratic process in Hong Kong, the former
foreign minister said: "If the advancement is too far or too fast,
as the Western democratic pattern, it is alleged to be
unacceptable for this stage of the Hong Kong story." He called on
different parties and sectors in the Hong Kong community to join
hands for continued success and prosperity of Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
