<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's New Airport to Have Flying Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new airport at
Chek Lap Kok, which is still under construction, will soon have
its first landing when American pilots carry out critical tests,
according to today's South China Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
A small jet airplane will be flown by two pilots from the
United States' Federal Aviation Administration in a month-long
series of tests, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The maiden landing is expected on February 17, more than a year
before the scheduled opening of the airport in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Civil Aviation Department chief electronic engineer
Leung Woon-yin said the new airport would be safer than Kai Tak
because different terrain allowed it to use higher precision
equipment for landing in all weather.
</P>
<P>
The tests, which will be repeated every four months, will set
radar equipment for guiding planes on to the runway, according to
the report. 
</P>
