<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Inflow Declines in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign exchange inflow through the
Bank of Zambia (BOZ) in 1996 declined drastically mainly due to a
halt slapped on balance of payment support by some donors and the
retention of 100 percent earnings by Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
This led to the country's outflow overshooting the inflow by 4.47
percent, according to the statistics from the country's Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange inflow amounted only to 432.118 million
US Dollars, of which 193.092 million dollars came from
non-government sources, and 153.227 million dollars from donors
as most bilateral donor countries froze aid to Zambia due to the
controversal constitutional amendment bill, which successfully
barred former President Kenneth Kaunda from running for the
presidency in the elections last November. And ZCCM contributed
85.799 million dollars to the inflow from January to March before
BOZ stopped selling foreign exchange to the market.
</P>
<P>
The total outflow was 451.443 million dollars, of which 169.581
million dollars went to service external debt, 33.786 million was
used by non-government services while 83.941 million dollars was for
government's other uses.
</P>
<P>
This means that the government once again overspent on its foreign
exchange inflow by 4.47 percent, but this was relatively much lower
than those of the previous years.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange inflow in 1995 was 758.562 million dollars
while outlow amounted to 1,338.842 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's foreign debt reduced to 6.573 billion dollars in
1996 from 7.288 billion dollars in 1991. enditem


