<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korean investments in
overseas securities hit 33.3 million U.S. dollars in 1996, a
six-fold increase over the previous year, the Korea Securities
Depository (KSD) said today.
</P>
<P>
The country's corporate and individual investments in foreign
securities markets included 22.09 million dollars in bonds, which
accounted for nearly two thirds of the total, 10.85 million dollars
in stocks and 360,000 dollars in mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
Investors have been focusing on better developed economies
since overseas transaction was allowed in July, 1994, the
organization said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 74.6 percent of the total investments, or 24.85
million dollars, went to the European Union countries, while 4.52
million dollars went to Hong kong and 3.41 million to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The organization added that the investors need more
up-to-the-minute information to better guide their overseas
investments. 
