<HEADLINE> Hawke Upbeat About Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Former Australian Prime
Minister Bob Hawke today expressed his full confidence in the
future of Hong Kong, whose economy, he believed, will continue to
prosper with increasing integration with the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
"I am basically optimistic about the future of Hong Kong,"
Hawke said at a luncheon hosted by the Australian Chamber of
Commerce here.
</P>
<P>
"I certainly and absolutely have no doubt about Hong Kong's
capacity, the capacity of its business leaders and workers, to
continue into the future to adapt to the economic challenges."
</P>
<P>
In retrospect to Hong Kong's economic progress, Hawke said Hong
Kong enjoyed a significant rise in economic prosperity in the
period of negotiating the Sino-British Joint Declaration which was
signed in 1984. The approach has been increasingly linked to
economic development on the Chinese mainland, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's GDP per capita reached 23,472 US dollars in 1995,
ranking second in the world. The dramatic growth has been
characterized by increasing integration with the mainland," Hawke
said, citing the large-scale relocation of manufacturing factories
from Hong Kong to southern China, and the huge flow of
cross-border investment.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong now is the single largest investor in China,
accounting for about 60 percent of the total external capital
realized in the country. Hawke estimated that nearly one third of
investment in Hong Kong's banking, properties and transport
sectors came from China.
</P>
<P>
In assessing Hong Kong's future, he pointed out that one must
also address the issue of how to see the future of China. Having
visited China many times, Hawke gave an overall view of the
Chinese economy, ranging from market reform to economic growth
rates and to agriculture produce and domestic savings. He believed
that the prospects for China are good. "It is not a question of
if, but when," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
