<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese More Open in Spouse Soliciting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- More than ten single men and
women in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, have
agreed to have their color photographs published in a local
newspaper as part of spouse soliciting advertisements.
</P>
<P>
Usually, spouse soliciting advertisements in China consist of
a brief text of self-introduction, and respondents can only make
contact with the advertiser via a designated person or matchmaking
center.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing-based "Xinhua Weekend" newspaper recently launched
a column entitled "Bridge Between Hearts", which offers free
spouse soliciting advertising to people who are willing to also
publish their personal photos.
</P>
<P>
More than ten local single people have already responded to the
bold idea. Song Weifeng, a local matchmaker in charge of the
column, said that several of them have quickly found prospective
partners.
</P>
<P>
"The photo has added more transparency to the advertisement,
and made the partner-seeking messages more popular than ordinary
ones," Song explained.
</P>
<P>
Local sociologists said that the change in spouse soliciting
advertising, along with thriving TV matchmaking in recent years,
indicates that Chinese people have become more open-minded in
marriage concepts after nearly two decades of reform and opening
up.  
</P>
