<HEADLINE> President Rawlings to Be Inaugurated in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Re-elected Ghanaian President
Jerry Rawlings and the parliament are due to be inaugurated in
capital Accra today, one month after the general elections,
said a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration marks the beginning of Rawlings's second term
of office, which, according to the country's constitution, must
also be his last.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings, 49, won the December 7 poll with 57.2 percent of
valid votes cast, while his party, the National Democratic
Congress (NDC), dominated the 200-seat parliament after having
won 133 of the 199 seats contested in legislative polls.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, even before the new parliament
convenes, its members have argued about the choice of speaker.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the People's Convention Party (PCP), the smaller of
two parties making up an opposition alliance, bitterly announced
the break of the coalition, complaining that its partner, the New
Patriotic Party (NPP), had deliberately marginalized the PCP.
</P>
<P>
Accra's political analysts said the NDC had been moving to
rally the support of the PCP's five members of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The NPP, the dominant force of the opposition with 60 seats in
parliament, has also argued with the government about the venue
of the presidential inauguration.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings first came to power in Ghana in a military coup in
1979 before ceding power to a civilian government later that
year. But in 1981, he staged another successful military coup to
topple the government and had since become head of state of the
west African country.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, Rawlings won the presidential election and the
newly-formed NDC swept legislative polls which were boycotted by
the opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
