<HEADLINE> China Calls for Britain to Settle Vietnamese Boat People Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Shen Guofang hopes that the British government would
solve the Vietnamese boat people issue completely and thoroughly
before July 1, this year, when China resumes its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong, and not throw any of the burden on the
future government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Shen made the remarks this afternoon at a press conference in
reply to a reporter's question concerning Vietnamese boat people's
request last November for a "human protection" decree from the
Supreme Court in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the issue of Vietnamese boat people
staying over in Hong Kong is a result of a wrong policy by the
British government, promising to take Hong Kong as the first
shelter harbor. The British government is unshirkablely
responsible for its settlement.
</P>
<P>
Shen said he hopes the British side will proceed from Hong
Kong's long-term prosperity, and the interests of the Hong Kong
residents and take effective measures to prevent the Vietnamese
boat people from getting into Hong Kong society.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese boat people, he said, are illegitimate
immigrants, and should be repatriated to where they came from in
line with international conventions.
</P>
<P>
In the past years, the British Hong Kong authorities sought
excuses many times to get them released, sending a wrong message
to the boat people, and hence obstructing the smooth progress of
repatriation work.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman warned that if the boat people were released once
again this time by abusing legal means, a large number of boat
people would enter Hong Kong society, bringing about a negative
impact on future repatriation work.
</P>
<P>
"We are seriously concerned about this issue, " he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
