<HEADLINE> Severe Punishment Warned for Fast Break in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Judicial Chief Mohammad
Yazdi warned of severe punishment for those who break the
sanctity of the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan, local Persian
daily Abrar reported today.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi requested all people to refrain from any behavior
dishonoring sacraments in public during Ramadan which falls on
January 11 this year. He said that Iranian courts would punish
the violators severely.
</P>
<P>
However, the judicial chief did not specify the
punishment. Specialists said that the punishment included lashes
and imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Islamic principles, those who violate
the rule will be punished with 60 whips.
</P>
<P>
According to the rule, any pretension of breaking the fast in
public is prohibited. All restaurants and coffee shops are
prohibited from serving from dawn to dusk.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan is the 9th month of the Islamic lunar year, observed
as sacred with fasting practiced daily from dawn to sunset.
</P>
