<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Guangdong to Alleviate Absolute Poverty by Year-End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South China's prosperous
Guangdong Province has vowed to alleviate absolute poverty this
year for the 600,000 people who now exist without enough to eat
and wear.
</P>
<P>
"We made considerable progress in reducing absolute poverty
last year and we want to alleviate it this year," said an official
of the province, which has a population of more than 60 million.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the province's totally destitute population
shrank by 390,000 in 1996, cutting the ratio of people without
enough food and clothing to the provincial population by 0.64
percentage points, to 0.96 percent by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Just ten years ago, Guangdong had four million people that did
not have enough of the basic necessities, or who had an annual
income of less than 250 yuan (about 30 US dollars in current
value) and a yearly grain consumption of less than 200 kg. And
there were another 14 million people under the more
broadly-defined poverty line, which covered those with an annual
income of less than 500 yuan.
</P>
<P>
As a showcase of the country's reform and opening-up policies,
Guangdong has outperformed most other Chinese provinces and
regions in terms of overall economic development. Its coastal
areas have become affluent.
</P>
<P>
However, its mountain-bound areas, where the greatest
concentration of poor people live, have lagged behind in economic
growth, sometimes by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, Guangdong has taken a number of serious
measures, including setting up special aid-the-poor funds,
tailoring annual examinations of local officials to poverty
relief, and issuing rules that oblige the more developed coastal
areas to help the less developed interior areas.
</P>
<P>
"We have made poverty alleviation part of our system," the
provincial official told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said that it could be a hard nut to alleviate the remaining
absolute poverty in the hilly and mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore we need to make an even greater effort for poverty
relief," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Total investment in the first group of poverty alleviation
projects this year has been set at 1.48 billion yuan, compared
with 152 million yuan last year, he said, adding that provincial
fiscal allocations for poverty relief increased by 200 million
yuan in the first half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said that money will be invested mainly in agricultural and
energy projects in the 16 poorest counties, to ensure that the
goal of alleviating absolute poverty will be accomplished this
year.
</P>
<P>
What can pose yet another challenge for Guangdong, a developed
area measured by Chinese standards, is that it has been ordered by
the State Council to help the poverty relief effort of neighboring
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, which has a large number of poor
people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0160 </DOCNO>
