<HEADLINE> China Faces Severe Challenge at Sydney Olympics, Wu Shaozu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- China, which clinched fourth
place on the medal table at the Atlanta Olympics last summer, will
face severe challenge in the 2000 Sydney Olympics, president of
the Chinese Olympic Committee Wu Shaozu said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
China got 16 gold medals, ahead of France, Italy and Australia
in Atlanta, but "we must make our minds clear that our position
face severe challenge from those countries, especially from host
Australia at Sydney," Wu told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Australia ranked fifth in the Atlanta Olympics with a total of
41 medals against China's 50.
</P>
<P>
"Australia has mapped a six-year sports developing plan, aiming
to enter top five places by leaving home 60 medals including 20
golds at the Sydney Olympics," said Wu, also a minister of the
Chinese State Physical Culture and Sports Commission.
</P>
<P>
Wu also said the China's Eighth National Games to be held in
Shanghai in October this year will be a preparation for both the
1998 Asian Games and 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The Eighth National Games will feature 28 sports events,
instead 45 of the Seventh National Games in Beijing, with 7000
athletes from 45 delegations participating.
</P>
<P>
"On July first, three months before the opening ceremony of the
national game is held, Hong Kong will return to the embrace of the
our motherland, and We welcome the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region to send its delegation to Shanghai,"
Wu said. 
