<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Sends Food, Medicine to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Ten nationals of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) today set sail for Iraq to deliver 25 tons of
milk and medicine to help ease the suffering of Iraqi children
under the U.N.-imposed sanctions.
</P>
<P>
It was the first such delivery by the UAE since the Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait in 1990, which strained the ties between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The 10 men, aboard a ship named Al Abbar at the country's
northern port of Kamriya, are expected to reach the southern Iraqi
port of Umm Qasr after a 40-hour trip, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The ship, owned by a local businessman, carried 17 tons of milk
for Children and eight tons of medicine, the value of which is
estimated at about 410,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
General Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid, Crown Prince of Dubai,
donated the food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The trip came after a November appeal by UAE President Sheikh
Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan for reconciliation with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Children's Fund said in November that 4,500
children were dying each month in Iraq due to the lack of food and
medicines since the 1990 Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed trade sanctions on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990, Iraq said the embargo has deprived it of cash to
buy food and medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Wins Less Overseas Shipbuilding Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea received orders for
142 ships weighing 6.93 million gross tons from overseas last
year, down 2.8 percent from the previous year, the Korea
Shipbuilders Association (KSA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The drop was due to foreign shipping firms' reluctance to build
new vessels for fear of a global slowdown in the shipping
industry, according to the KSA.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, South Korean shipbuilders received orders for 194
vessels weighing 7.13 million gross tons, up 11.9 percent from the
6.37 million gross tons recorded in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Despite the drop in overseas orders, the country's total ship
construction last year amounted to 7.74 million gross tons, up
36.8 percent over the 5.66 million gross tons registered in 1995.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the second largest shipbuilder in the world
following Japan with an annual shipbuilding capacity of 8.5
million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
