<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulation Helps People Lodge Complaints in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A new regulation to help people
lodge official complaints has been approved by the Standing
Committee of the Zhejiang Provincial People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The regulation, which will come into force on February 1,
mainly consists of stipulations about the rights and
responsibilities of people who make complaints, and the
responsibilities and procedures of government departments in
dealing with complaints from the people.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the implementation of the regulation will help
protect the legitimate rights and interests of people who lodge
complaints, and improve the work of departments concerned.
</P>
<P>
An official says that by means of writing letters and making
calls, ordinary citizens involve themselves in the management of
state and social affairs. Their efforts play an increasingly
important role in the country's democratization process.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that departments concerned received 200,000
complaints in 1996, mostly focused on enterprise reform, urban
construction and public security.
</P>
<P>
The regulation provides that township and neighborhood-level
government departments set up special work units to offer a
broader access to ordinary citizens who wish to make
complaints. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy Proposes Compromise on Further Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross
is proposing a compromise on further Israeli troop pullbacks in
the West Bank in a bid to clear the last obstacle blocking a
Hebron deal.
</P>
<P>
Ross held several meetings Monday with Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem and then with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat in Bethlehem to intensify his efforts to bridge
the remaining gap.
</P>
<P>
The last obstacle blocking the long-delayed Hebron deal is the
Palestinian demand for setting a timetable for Israeli troop
redeployments in the rural areas in the West Bank following the
Hebron pullback.
</P>
<P>
Arafat wanted Israel to promise to carry out further
redeployments according to the Oslo accords, which stipulate that
the redeployments should be completed by next September. But in
the secret Arafat-Netanyahu summit held Sunday morning, Netanyahu
only promised that Israel would complete the pullbacks before
spring 1999.
</P>
<P>
Israeli sources said Ross is seeking a compromise between the
Palestinian and Israeli demands. It remains unclear whether
Ross' proposed date would be the midway point between the two
dates: the summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that Ross would leave here once again
within the next few days if he fails to convince the two sides
to reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
"I remain hopeful we will see an agreement soon, but I can't
predict when," Ross said after meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
English language daily the Jerusalem Post reported that
U.S. President Bill Clinton linked his invitation to Arafat for a
visit to Washington with the Hebron deal. The U.S. has told Arafat
that failure to conclude a deal could influence negatively on his
relations with the White House.
</P>
<P>
While Clinton has not linked his invitation to Netanyahu to
the conclusion of the Hebron deal, the U.S. president apparently
prefers to see such a deal forged before receiving Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
To allay the concern about each other's future violations of
agreements, the U.S. is considering writing "letters of
assurance" to both sides, as it did on the eve of the 1991
Madrid peace conference, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
