<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Find 3,500-year-old Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
excavated a complete section of wall which was built 3,500 years
ago to protect an ancient city.
</P>
<P>
The wall, in Yanshi in central China's Henan Province, belonged
to the Shang Dynasty (16th-11th century BC).
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said that the 2.3-meter-high wall is surrounded
by a six-meter-deep moat. Within the city are scattered a number
of tombs, pottery kilns and sewers.
</P>
<P>
The researchers have also found tracks of wheels, proving that the
country's history of using carts was 300 years earlier than
previously believed.
</P>
<P>
The city's protective wall was first excavated in 1983 and
since then archeologists have found five city gates and three
palace-like buildings.
</P>
<P>
The city was believed to be built in the early days of the
Shang Dynasty, when Chinese society was still at a stage of
slave-owning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
