<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Breakthrough in Rice Structure by Chinese Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
produced the world's first high-definition DNA "fingerprint" of
rice, the country's stable food.
</P>
<P>
They say the breakthrough will have a major impact on the
genetic breeding of new strains of grain crops in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have been able to construct a complete
high-definition graph of rice genes, a so-called DNA fingerprint.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough was made at the National Gene Research Center
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences after three years of effort,
according to a press conference held by the State Science and
Technology Commission, the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the
Shanghai Municipal Government. The scientific team was headed by
researcher Hong Guofan.
</P>
<P>
The high definition of the graph, measuring some 120,000
nucleic acid, makes possible the direct measurement of the DNA
structure in order, according to scientists.
</P>
<P>
The graph contains 565 genetic markers, and the distance
between many of the markers are already clear. It will enable
scientists to obtain rice genes faster.
</P>
<P>
The graph contains some 100 universal genetic markers, some of
which are already known to be universal in the genes of some major
crops, including barley, oat, wheat, corn, sorghum and sugarcane.
</P>
<P>
The graph will have great influence on the genetic breeding of
crops, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
It was described as the most influential achievement in recent
years in the basic research in China, according to the press
conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
