<HEADLINE> Task Force Formed to Fight Crime in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A police task force has been
formed in Kenya to fight crime in the capital of Nairobi,
according to a Kenya Times report today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that plainclothes police officers selected
from more than 45 police divisions all over the country have been
arriving in the city and are at present assembled in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The assignment of the task force, mostly drawn from the
Criminal Investigation Department, was seen as the first of its
kind planned by the newly-appointed Police Commissioner, Duncan
Wachira.
</P>
<P>
The task force, which is under the command of Zachariah
Cheruiyot, a seasonal crime buster, was dissuaded from receiving
bribes and using their guns unless it is absolutely
necessary.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest police report, armed crime incidents in
Nairobi had risen to 470 in the third quarter of last year,
compared with 331 and 373 in the first and second quarters.
</P>
<P>
Car-hijackings in the capital had reached an all-time high of
420 incidents for a three-month period ending last September, up
from 227 and 201 in the first two quarters last year
respectively. 
</P>
