<HEADLINE> Farmers Make "Gold" From Stones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- For farmers in Linqu County, east
China's Shandong Province, the old saying "Touching a stone and
turning it into gold" is no longer a dream.
</P>
<P>
The county's 8,000 farming families are making money by
quarrying and selling stones and stone products.
</P>
<P>
Located to the north of Yimeng Mountains, the county boasts
more than 2,000 high and low hills and rich stone resources,
including fossilized pre-history beings, and basalt and sapphire
formed during the Tertiary Period.
</P>
<P>
Quarrying and selling stones and stone products became popular
in the county just two years ago, and has attracted hundreds of
thousands of stone fans.
</P>
<P>
Every five days there is a stone market where people can spend
two or three yuan buying a stone product. But occasionally they
would have to pay at least 100,000 yuan for a rare specimen.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers make colorful stone products which feature not
only human beings, animals and birds, rivers and mountains, but
also legendary stories.
</P>
<P>
By last year Linqu County had opened more than 500 stone
stores, and there were 32 villages specializing in the selling of
unique and rare stones.
</P>
<P>
The county government has invested more than 10 million yuan
building a unique stone street, a stone market and a rare stone
museum. The projects produce at least 100 million yuan a year for
the county. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
