<HEADLINE> Philippine Government, MILF Open Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The peace panels of the
Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
today opened their peace talks in Maguindanao province, the
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Fortunato Abat, chief government peace negotiator,
shook hands and hugged with his MILF counterpart Moner Bajunaid
and other MILF representatives shortly before a simple rite
marking the start of the first technical working group meeting
between the two panels.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was held in Sultan Kudarat town of the
province, is expected to lay the ground rules for a formal
ceasefire and set the agenda for their formal peace talks which
will start after the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
In his opening statement, Abat expressed optimism that despite
the "enormous task ahead of us, we find strength on the belief
that we are all here because we all want peace."
</P>
<P>
He said he will recommend to President Fidel Ramos the
extension of the government-imposed ceasefire for another 60 days
in respect to the observance of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
Bajunaid, on the other hand, cited the significance of holding
the talks in this town "where Sultan Mohammad Dipatuan Kudarat
once ruled and drove away foreign invaders in defense of Islam in
Mindanao."
</P>
<P>
He said the MILF presence in today's historic meeting "comes at
an appropriate time as we begin the year 1997, we venture in
taking the first step of finding a just and political solution to
the conflict" between the government and the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Citing previous attempts of settling the conflict with the
regime of late President Ferdinand Marcos and in 1987 with the
Corazon Aquino administration, Bajunaid hoped that today's efforts
will bring the two sides closer towards a genuine and lasting
peace.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will end tomorrow with both panels issuing a joint
press communique on what had been discussed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
