<HEADLINE> Shangdong combating Cotton Diseases and Insect Pests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- More of China's cotton growing
land is escaping from disease and insects, and there is much less
pesticide pollution.
</P>
<P>
The achievement has been made possible in Wenshang County, east
China's Shandong Province, with assistance from the Asia
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to a local official, 75,000 hectares of cotton land
has become disease free and has suffered no insect pests since a
control project under the Asia Development Bank was launched four
years ago in Wenshang county.
</P>
<P>
"So far, the project has saved 7.5 million US dollars in
addition to creating a better ecological environment," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Wenshang county is one of four sites where the bank launched
its worldwide cotton disease and insects pest control projects.
</P>
<P>
Differing from the traditional chemicals, the new projects use
more agricultural, biological, physical and machinery means of
control.
</P>
<P>
"I am very satisfied with the achievements at Wenshang, and the
experience should be shared by more places," said Asia Development
Bank official, S. Ramaswamy.
</P>
<P>
According to an official at the provincial government of
Shandong, the techniques used in cotton disease and insect pest
control in Wenshang will soon be spread throughout Shandong
Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
