<HEADLINE> Thai-Foreign Ventures Approach for ASEAN Privileges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Five Thai-foreign joint ventures
are seeking entry into the ASEAN industrial cooperation scheme
which provides significant tax privileges to expand their
businesses, according to the Thai Industry Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
The five groups are Matsushita-Panasonic, Indo Rama, Nippon
Denso, Volvo, and Toyota in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Matsushita in Thailand is seeking to barter electric fans and
parts with Malaysia, Indonesia and the Philippines, while Indo
Rama to barter plastic drinking water bottles and vegetable oil
with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Denso wants to barter auto parts with Indonesia and the
Philippines, while Volvo and Toyota want to barter the products
with Malaysia, Indonesia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, eligible companies could enjoy tariffs
ranging 0-5 percent on sales of products with the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The scheme was a cooperate initiative by ASEAN's private sector
as part of the group's efforts to cut production costs and
reinforce the competitiveness of regional industries.
</P>
<P>
According to the scheme, companies in ASEAN in which foreigners
have not less than 30 percent stakes may apply for the privileges.
Candidates short of this requirement also could enter the scheme
if they meet other requirements set by individual ASEAN members.
</P>
</TEXT>
