<HEADLINE> Grain Bases Report Good Harvests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Grain-producing Provinces in
various parts of China have reported good grain harvests in 1996.
</P>
<P>
North China's Hebei Province set an all-time record, gathering
27.7 billion kg of grain last year.
</P>
<P>
A provincial agricultural official attributed the good harvest
to the application of modern agro-science. The province spread 30
kinds of new agro-techniques on nine million hectares of land last
year.
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region harvested
15.9 billion kg of grain last year, 370 million kg more than the
1995 figure, despite a serious drought.
</P>
<P>
The output of sugar cane, oil-bearing crops, animal by-products
and aquatic products, also registered big increases.
</P>
<P>
The per capita net income of farmers rose to 1,680 yuan last
year, 234 yuan over the previous year's figure.
</P>
<P>
Gansu Province, in northwest China, achieved an all-round
agricultural development in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Its output of grain rose to 8.2 billion kg, 10 percent more
than that in the peak year of 1993. The output value of some
pillar industries in rural areas totalled 13.2 billion yuan,
representing a 6.8 percent rise. Farmers' annual net income surged
by 24.4 percent to 1,100 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province, which used to be a grain importer in
northeast China, secured 16.6 billion kg of grain last year. Its
outputs of vegetables, fruit, meat, eggs and milk also set new
records.
</P>
<P>
So far it has not only been self-sufficient in grain supplies,
but has also been able to export grain to other Chinese provinces.
</P>
<P>
The island province of Hainan produced 350,000 tons of meat in
1996, 9.7 percent up from previous year's output, 460,000 tons of
aquatic products, up by 6.4 percent, 1.9 million tons of
vegetables, up by 17 percent, and 450,000 tons of fruit, up by 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the total output of grain reached 480 million tons,
which set another historical record, better than the good harvest
in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Save Babu the Elephant's Trunk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhengzhou, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in China came to the
rescue after Babu the elephant accidentally severed his own trunk.
</P>
<P>
In a complicated 17-hour operation, they successfully stitched
back Babu's trunk, enabling the huge animal to feed itself once
more.
</P>
<P>
Veterinary surgeons in Zhengzhou, capital city of central
China's Henan province, sent an urgent plea to a top limb
transplant surgeon at a Chinese hospital, asking for help.
</P>
<P>
The replantation expert at a Zhengzhou hospital dashed
immediately to the city's zoo after the call, while veterinary
surgeons from Shanghai, Shenzhen and Beijing rushed to the city by
air with special anaesthetics, and to help in the surgery.
</P>
<P>
Now well on the road to recovery, Babu has become an instant
star at Zhengzhou Zoo, as thousands of men, women and children
follow the drama.
</P>
<P>
Many people are visiting the zoo daily to see Babu in a public
show of care and concern for the 14 year old elephant.
</P>
<P>
The drama started three months ago when Babu had his trunk
hanging on a window with iron grating five-meters above ground. He
was leaning on the railing playing with female companion across a
fence.
</P>
<P>
When Babu tried to withdraw his trunk, it became trapped by the
iron window grating. The harder Babu tried, the more his trunk
became squeezed, causing acute pain. The intense pain caused the
three-ton distressed animal to fall, severing a length of his
trunk.
</P>
<P>
When zoo staff realized what had happened they quickly alerted
a medical team.
</P>
<P>
The major problem during the operation was with the level of
anaesthesia. Giving too little anaesthetic would mean the elephant
moving around, while too much would make the patient lay flat on
the ground, with its heart and lungs pressed by its own weight.
</P>
<P>
The 17-hour operation was successfully undertaken in the zoo's
elephant hall with a surgeon and over 20 assistants.
</P>
<P>
Doctors reported that tears ran down Babu's face during the
operation as his female friend tried to comfort and console her
sick companion. She continually stretched her own trunk from her
own adjoining compound towards Babu to try to gently stroke him.
</P>
<P>
But Babu quickly moved away the operation instruments and
bandages near the wound after he regained consciousness.
</P>
<P>
Doctors then had to conduct another replantation operation on
the elephant.
</P>
<P>
Babu, whose trunk was shortened by 40 centimeters, could use it
again to place a cabbage into his mouth less than 100 days after
the operation.
</P>
<P>
The elephant now has a better relationship with his keeper
after being hand-fed with delicious food at least 400 times a day
during the post-operative period.
</P>
<P>
Babu has been a hot topic in the city during the past three
months, with city government officials visiting him. Ordinary
citizens, including people who seldom visited the zoo, and
tourists, have shown concern for his desperate plight.
</P>
<P>
A father, visiting the zoo with his child said, "We are very
sad at the news that the elephant had its trunk severed. It is
just like when a friend suffers an illness. So we have come here
to visit Babu."
</P>
<P>
A two-year-old boy, accompanied by his family, took his money
saving box to the zoo to donate his money to buy delicious food
for the elephant.
</P>
<P>
He mother said, "When the boy learned the news, he was very sad
and asked the family, "Does he feel pain? Can we do something for
him?"
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the zoo believe that Babu will fully recover and
have a normal life with a special training.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairean Rebels Accuse S. African Mercenaries of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebels have
accused South African and Angolan mercenaries as well as the
French troops aiding Kinshasa's government troops.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are preparing for meeting a counter-attack by the
government troops, South Africa's local newspaper the Star
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Rebel chief Laurent-Desire Kabila, speaking in the rebel-held
eastern town of Goma, said there are 1,000 French troops as well
as South African and Angolan mercenaries in Kisangani, a city 500
kilometres northwest of Goma.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate reaction from the South African
government, but the claim was immediately denied by Paris.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the French Defense Ministry said there were no
French troops in Zaire, except for five paramilitary officers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, European diplomats based in Kisangani said they had
seen no sign of French or other foreign troops there.
</P>
<P>
Kisangani is a strategic town that would be a major gathering point
for a possible counter-attack by Zaire's government troops.
</P>
<P>
Kabila stressed there were also mercenaries from a South
African company, the Executive Outcome. He did not give numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
