<HEADLINE> Big Rewards As Beijing Continues Anti-Porn Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's anti-pornography and
anti-piracy fights were fruitful in the past
month, as officials netted 24 suspects.
</P>
<P>
And with people in China's capital being offered rewards of up
to 100,000 yuan for informing on wholesalers and pedlars of
pirated and pornographic VCD's, the successes are set to continue.
</P>
<P>
Special telephone hotlines have been opened in the Chinese
capital to encourage members of the public to spill the beans on
criminals.
</P>
<P>
Beijing authorities last month seized 24 suspects and 1,700
pornographic books, 33,198 pirated books, 3,950 pirated tapes,
3,300 pirated and pornographic CD's, 5,083 pornographic
and illegal video compact discs, as well as 2,900 illegal video
tapes.
</P>
<P>
It brought the total number of seizures to 55,900 illegal
laser discs, compact discs, video tapes and other electronic
publications this winter.
</P>
<P>
And several syndicates, selling and pirating books, video and
audio products, have been smashed, according to the Beijing
Evening News.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a massive nationwide "winter strike hard " on
criminal acts and criminals, following the successful anti-crime
campaign which was launched last year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing authorities have vowed to reward anyone who reports on
illegal trading of VCDs, a new measure this year to combat local
copyright piracy.
</P>
<P>
The rewards ranged from 10,000 yuan (1,025 US dollars) to
100,000 yuan (12,048 US dollars) in line with the number of
illegal VCDs confiscated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
