<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt for Gender Equality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is making
efforts to create an environment of gender equality and
subsequent integration of women in national development.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made by Austin Mweemba, Permanent Secretary in
the Administration Division at Cabinet Office, in Kafue, south of
capital Lusaka, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government's efforts have been highlighted by the creation
of the Gender in Development Division at Cabinet Office, said
Mweemba while officially opening a training workshop for gender
focal point persons in ministries and provinces.
</P>
<P>
Mweemba noted that the government has made headway in
alleviating inherent gender biases and other legislative
obstacles that impinge upon the participation of women in
national issues.
</P>
<P>
"I am glad to say that most gender biases have been removed
from our laws and the government has now shifted its focus to
biases in administrative processes and procedures," Mweemba said.
</P>
<P>
However, Mweemba observed that women in Zambia have still
continued to be disadvantaged in economic and social development
by prohibitive social and legislative laws.
</P>
<P>
He said that discriminatory legislation, coupled with cultural
biases and taboos, have continued to plague women's full
potential for development. Women are also haunted in their
development efforts by such vices as inaccessible credit
facilities and land. A majority of them are devastated by
property grabbing.
</P>
<P>
These vices have frustrated women from realizing their full
potential in educational, professional, political and economic
spheres, Mweemba said.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of gender focal point persons in all
ministries and provinces is expected to provide the government
with a clear avenue through which it will be able to propagate
special gender programs which promote women's rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
