<HEADLINE> Effective Reform Ensures Ample Supply of Foodstuff in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's food supplies in
1996 were sufficient and prices remained stable as a result of
effective reform measures, including price-liberalization schemes.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's largest city, has an urban population of
about 10 million. Each year the city consumes over 1.4 million
tons of vegetables, 350,000 tons of pork, 1.1 billion kilograms of
eggs, 120,000 tons of fresh water fish, and over 600,000 tons of
rice.
</P>
<P>
In a move to meet growing demand and prevent the production
initiative of the farmers from dwindling, the municipal government
last year began to introduce bold measures to remove government
controls, and let prices float according to market demand.
</P>
<P>
Another effective measure accountable for the stable market was
the reform of financial subsidies. While in the past, subsidies
were provided in a broad way, now the policy has become more
selective.
</P>
<P>
The subsidies now mainly go to four areas, including the
municipal government macro-economic fund; production support
funding; a development fund for State-owned enterprises; and
funding for the operation of enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
