<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe May Not Meet EU Beef Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is unlikely to meet its
European Union quota for beef exports, losing hundreds of
millions of U.S. Dollars in export revenue, according to the
Daily Herald today.
</P>
<P>
This is because the Cold Storage Company (CSC) is still
"hard-pressed" for slaughter stock despite offering premiums to
cattle producers.
</P>
<P>
The high prices that top-quality beef fetches in Europe bring
CSC, which has the monopoly for European exports and has the only
EU-inspected cattle abattoirs, about 40 million U.S. Dollars a
year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year CSC offered premiums to producers of
suitable cattle to attract more into its export abattoirs. But
these have failed to bring in the required amount of cattle.
</P>
<P>
Cattle producers in both the commercial and smallholder
sectors were hammered by the drought in 1992 and subsequent poor
seasons. They have found it hard to rebuild the national herd
since available finance is either very expensive or in very short
supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
