<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soft Landing Is must to Check Overheated Economic Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- China's economy scored a
successful soft landing in 1996, which is a must to beat
overheated economic expansion, an article by two top economists
said in today's "People's Daily".
</P>
<P>
China's economy had a successful soft landing in 1996, thanks
to countermeasures taken to combat overheated economic expansion
in the early years of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the economic growth peak and bottom from 1991
to 1996 was 4.5 percentage points, the smallest fluctuation since
the establishment of New China in 1949, said the article.
</P>
<P>
The article was written by Liu Guoguang and Liu Shucheng, two
economists at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The authors noted that the country had a fast development in
its reform, opening-up and modernization drive from 1991 to early
1993. This was quickly followed by an overheated economic
expansion, and chaotic economic order, especially a financial
disorder, coupled with many other problems cropping up in China's
economic life.
</P>
<P>
To change that situation, China, under the leadership by the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee headed by President
Jiang Zemin, has fully implemented Deng Xiaoping's theory of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics and the Party's
basic lines of taking economic construction as the central task.
</P>
<P>
A series of measures were worked out to tighten macro-economic
control and launch a soft landing in national economic operations.
</P>
<P>
The country carefully implemented soft-landing measures and
achieved success after three years of efforts.
</P>
<P>
The two economists warned that China learned bitter lessons
from its "hard landing," which caused steep ups and downs in the
economy as a result of seeking rapid economic growth only in late
1950s.
</P>
<P>
In 1958, the country had the highest economic growth rate of 22
percent, but had negative economic growth rates from 1960 to 1962,
with 1961 having the lowest economic growth rate of minus 29.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
China incurred losses totaling 178 billion yuan (one
U.S. dollars now equals to 8.3 Chinese yuan) during the economic
"hard landing" from 1958 to 1962. The country regained its
economic strength in 1964, and its national economic
development was thus delayed by seven years.
</P>
<P>
An abortive "soft landing" was just as harmful as a "hard
landing", said the two economists.
</P>
<P>
China had an unsuccessful soft landing in 1986, despite the
fact that measures were taken to beat an overheated economy from
1982 to 1985, driving inflation skyrocketing, and forcing the
country to practice economic austerity programs from 1989 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
The article added that China should continue to stick to a
comparatively tight money control policy, curb inflation, and
secure a stable and relaxed economic environment, and vigorously
promote two shifts, namely, a shift from a planned economic
structure to a market economic structure and a shift from
extensive operation to intensive operation, with the purpose of
pushing ahead economic construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Company Finds Overseas Jobs for Its Laid-offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- An industrial corporation in east
China's Jiangsu Province has found jobs in the Republic of Korea
for 60 of its laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The 60 former workers at the Asia Group, a commercial
corporation in Suzhou with a 1996 retail turnover of 510 million
yuan (about 61 million US dollars), were among the staffers who
lost their jobs because the company rationalized its production
methods.
</P>
<P>
After negotiations a ROK corporation has signed one-year
contracts with the 60 laid-off workers, who are all under 40 years
old and capable of doing their new jobs in aquatic product
processing.
</P>
<P>
The ROK company is expected to arrange accommodation for the
workers and pay each of them 20,000-yuan (2,400 US dollars)
after-tax salary in the year.
</P>
<P>
The commercial group's chairman, Gong Guojun, said that it is a
new and bold attempt to make arrangements for laid-off staff.
