<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Celebrate Chinese Lunar New Year with Chimes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- China's capital city of Beijing
will mark the Chinese Lunar New Year with the chimes of an ancient
bell, helped by the wonders of modern sound technology.
</P>
<P>
Many residents in the capital stil bemoan the ban on
firecrackers which ensured a noisy, but dangerous, start to the
traditional Spring Festival celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The fireworks and firecrackers were finally silenced in 1993,
ending a centuries old tradition.
</P>
<P>
Now lovers of noise can pin back their ears with relish, as the
city's Drum Tower in the northeastern part of downtown Beijing,
joins in the fun.
</P>
<P>
For hundreds of years the 63-ton bronze bell, second only in
size to one in Moscow, has rung out throughout Beijing. It was
cast in the 15th century and during the Ming and Qing Dynasties --
spanning 1368 to 1911 -- Beijingers heard the 108 chimes every
morning and evening.
</P>
<P>
The sprawl of Beijing and the building of sound-blocking
skyscrapers have partly numbed the chimes.
</P>
<P>
Now four giant pnuematic loudspeakers have been added to boom
out the sounds of the chimes across a radius of ten kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Another four jumbo speakers will be installed in the south of
the city to relay the tolling of the bell even farther afield.
</P>
<P>
The chime was given a dress rehearsal on New Year's Eve to
provide a countdown for the start of 1997. Thousands of families
braved treacherous road conditions to head to the drum tower for
the midnight chime.
</P>
<P>
Now many people in Beijing plan to mark the traditional
Chinese new year, the country's biggest festival and time of
family reunions, by listening to the 108 chimes, just like ancient
Beijingers had done for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
Xu Chunyu arrived at the Drum Tower by a taxi from her home 20
kilometers away to attend the special New Year's Eve gathering, a
novelty for many young Beijing residents.
</P>
<P>
"I have been told of it by old people, today I heard it
myself," she said, "the pleasant bell ringing brought me a feeling
of luck for the future."
</P>
<P>
Bell-making and bell-ringing at celebrations are traditional
cultures in China, with the oldest bells being made during the
10th century BC.
</P>
<P>
 The bell chimes will never again drift as far as in ancient
times, said Tianjing, a research fellow with the Institute of
Acoustics of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Celebrate Chinese Lunar New Year with Chimes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu Xiangyuan, deputy director of the Beijing Commission of
Science and Technology, and also the co-sponsor of the function,
said the chimes will provide the new year atmosphere which has
been tempered by the ban on fireworks from 1993.
</P>
<P>
To make the chimes audible to as many people as possible, Ma
Dayou, CAS academician and an authoritative scholar in acoustics,
suggested Zhu solve the problem with the help of four large
pneumatic loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
The attempt was backed by the municipal government and is
expected to be an important event during a series of celebrations
for the Chinese New Year.
</P>
<P>
A snowfall decorated the Chinese capital at the end of
1996. But the traffic chaos caused by icy roads did not damp the
enthusiasm among Beijing people to listen to the chimes.
</P>
<P>
Wang and his family, who live in the western suburban
Shijingshan District, made their way to the Drum Tower.
</P>
<P>
"My home is too far away from here," Wang said, "but I really
think that attending this ceremony will bring all the family good
luck in the coming new year."
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the coldness on new year's eve helped to make the
sounds of the chimes reach farther afield.
</P>
<P>
"The efforts have combined ancient culture and modern
technologies. I believe we will have a better effect at Chinese
New Year's Eve."
</P>
<P>
Another four loudspeakers will be added on high ground in the
southern downtown, ensuring more people to hear the 108 chimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
