<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Residents Required to Donate Blood Once Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing, capital of east China's
Jiangsu Province, has passed a regulation on blood donations,
which will go into effect on April 1.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation approved by the local legislature,
each healthy permanent resident, male aged between 18 and 55 and
female aged between 18 and 50, has a duty to donate blood once
five years.
</P>
<P>
And each transient resident, who has stayed in the city for
more than one year, should assume their duty to voluntarily donate
blood.
</P>
<P>
The regulation in the economically booming province also
specifies responsibilities of local medical and blood collection
departments.
</P>
<P>
Those who supply substandard blood to patients will be
punished, including warnings, fines, compensation and being
brought before the law courts.
</P>
<P>
The measure is part of a long-running nationwide campaign to
urge people to volunteerly donate their blood to help in
blood-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
China's State Council, the cabinet, has just issued Regulations
on the Management of Blood Products to help prevent and control
diseases spread by transfused blood and blood products, and
ensuring the quality of blood products.
</P>
<P>
The 5,000-word regulations detail the procedures for blood
collection, control measures over units that manufacture and
manage blood products, supervisional mechanisms and rigorous
punishments against violators.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, another 10 provincial and 11 city legislative bodies
or governments have issued local regulations on blood donation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
