<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Hold Referendum on Devolution Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka government has
decided to hold a referendum if the main opposition United
National Party (UNP) does not support its devolution proposals.
</P>
<P>
The government needs a two-third majority to have the proposals
passed in Parliament and this could be obtained only with the
support of the UNP, Minister of Constitutional Affairs G. L.
Peiris Monday told local press in Matara in Southern province, 150
kilometers from Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Select Committee had met 62 times to discuss
the proposals last year. But there were differences of opinion in
areas such as land allocation, police power, oceanic rights and
foreign grants, he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNP had not opposed these proposals at the Select
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The devolution package announced by the president in August
1995 aims to resolve the long-standing ethnic crisis in the
country. It contains proposals for redemarcation of North and East
provinces and for extending more power to Tamils in these
provinces.  
</P>
