<HEADLINE> IFC Finances Fertilizer Output in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today signed an agreement to provide 18 million
U.S. dollars in loans to Engro Chemical Pakistan Ldt.
</P>
<P>
The funding will assist Engro to retrofit its gas-based ammonia
urea plant in order to improve energy efficiency, increase
capacity, and reduce emissions.
</P>
<P>
Engro is the country's second largest producer of urea with a
21 percent share of the local market. The company's original
manufacturing plant, with an annual capacity of 268,000 metric
tons of urea, was built in the 1960s. With a loan assistance in
1991, Engro expanded its plant's capacity to 600,000 tons of urea
annually.
</P>
<P>
The company has since completed a further debottlenecking to
750,000 tons a year. The 59-million-dollar retrofit project,
expected to be completed in April 1998, will enhance the plant's
annual capacity to 850,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The IFC's financing consists of a loan of 9 million dollars for
its own account and a syndicated loan of 9 million dollars for the
accounts of participating partners.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and also the
largest multilateral source of equity and loan financing for
private sector in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
