<HEADLINE> China Discovers New Proof of Nanjing Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The original version of a book
that recorded brutal crimes committed by Japanese soldiers in
China during the World War II has been found in Hefei, capital of
east China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
Historians said that the discovery of the book has provided new
evidence for the infamous Nanjing Massacre, which occurred between
late 1937 and early 1938 following the Japanese occupation of this
east China city.
</P>
<P>
The book, entitled "What War Means -- The Japanese Atrocities
in China," was written by H.J. Timperley, an overseas
correspondent for the British newspaper "Manchester Herald."
Timperley was in China in the late 1930s and witnessed the bloody
massacre in Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
The earliest translation of this book, published in China in
1938, was found by a retired worker who was sorting out the
belongings of his late father.
</P>
<P>
In the foreword, Timperley said that he was prompted to write
this book after the Japanese army prevented him from sending his
stories on the massacre back to England.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Chengshan, curator of the museum in memory of Nanjing
Massacre victims, said that his museum has only an incomplete copy
of the book.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that after the fall of Nanjing,
Japanese troops launched a mass killing of disarmed Chinese
soldiers and civilians. The number of victims has been estimated
at 300,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
