<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Lushan Listed as World Heritage Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Mount Lushan in east China's
Jiangxi Province has been listed as a World Heritage Site by the
United Nation's Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
It is the first Chinese cultural resort to be listed as a World
Heritage Site, and there are 16 Chinese tourist attractions
already on the prestige list. These include Mount Huangshan, the
Great Wall, the Forbidden City, Mogao Grottoes in Dunhuang,
Jiuzhaigou and Huanglong.
</P>
<P>
The World Heritage Center believes the combination of nature
and culture, which features the Chinese national flavor and
history, is the reason why the mountain has been chosen.
</P>
<P>
Lushan, located along China's longest Yangtze River, is famous
for its beautiful natural scenery, Buddhist and Taoist temples,
and rich cultural and historic backgrounds, which have lasted for
more than 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
In its history, some 30 Chinese emperors visited the mountain
or wrote in honor of it. There are over 600 European-style villas
on the mountain which were built in the early years of this
century.
</P>
<P>
Lushan applied for the listing over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
China signed the World Heritage Convention in 1985 and has
submitted a tentative list, including 58 sites, to the heritage
center during the next five to ten years as possible future World
Heritage Sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
