Mount Hulishan, which was set up in the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the show intend to set up a cannon museum in the
fort, and so far they have collected more than 50 old Chinese
cannons which were used in the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Collectors from Singapore have promised to provide the show
with nearly 100 old cannons which were made in Europe and other
Asian countries, including one miniature cannon with a
ten-centimeter-long barrel. Most have a high collecting value.
</P>
<P>
Experts say it is the first time that so many cannons have gone
on show in the country. 
