<HEADLINE> Rural Areas in East China Province on Massive Construction Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The burgeoning construction drive
in villages and towns in rural areas of east China's Fujian
Province over the past five years has provided new housing, roads,
telecommunication lines and water and power supplies for hundreds
of thousands of families in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, Fujian has injected 48.2 billion yuan (about 5.8
billion US dollars) into such construction projects. With the
investment, houses were built covering a total floor space of 120
million square meters, enabling 700,000 families to move into new
homes.
</P>
<P>
On the average, a farmer in the province currently has 24
square meters of floor space, and 35 percent of the people in the
rural areas have access to running water.
</P>
<P>
Fujian was actively involved in rural planning, and recently
drafted blueprints for the expansion of 507 towns and 8,169
villages.
</P>
<P>
Various areas have been urged to use land resources
economically and curb encroachment on cultivated land. In Jinshan
Village of Putian County, workers have torn down 212 old houses
and built new apartments on the foundations of the former
homes. Over the past decade, no new land has been taken for the
construction of new houses in the village.
</P>
<P>
Fujian has both mountainous and coastal areas, and has chosen
to focus on the development of ten towns along the
coast. Meanwhile, in the out-of-the-way villages in mountainous
areas which have adverse natural conditions, the province plans to
resettle 100,000 people into villages with better living
conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
