<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Set up Four More Industrial Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Four new export processing zones
(EPZS) are going to be set up in Bangladesh by the private
entrepreneurs, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
proposals for developing the EPZS or industrial parks were
being scrutinized by a cell at the prime minister's office, the
sources said, adding those proposals would be cleared soon in line
with the recently enacted private export processing zones act,
1996.
</P>
<P>
One of the EPZS would be developed in Chittagong, this
country's largest port city, by South Korean entrepreneurs, while
the others would be set up by local businessmen in Comilla and
Mymensingh districts, they added.
</P>
<P>
Korea's leading industrial group Youngone, which already has
huge investments in industries of this country's state-run Dhaka
and Chittagong EPZS, would have the major stake in that venture.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government set up the two industrial parks in
early 80s with a view to attracting foreign investments for
setting up 100 percent export-oriented industries by offering
one-stop services to foreign entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The industries in EPZS also enjoy facilities like a tax holiday
up to 12 years, duty-free import of raw materials and a ban on
trade union activity.
</P>
<P>
Officials at Bangladesh export processing zones authority said
exports from the country's two EPZS registered significant rise
during the past several years and this was what had prompted the
government to develop two other state-run EPZS in Gazipur and
Khulna districts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
