package of thrift to bring about a one-percent cut in the current
account deficit from last year's 8.2 percent (335.7 billion baht,
or 13.43 billion dollars) of gross domestic product (GDP), to 7.2
percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
After being briefed on Monday by senior officials of the
Commerce Ministry, the Bank of Thailand and the Budget Bureau,
about measures to spur the economy and rein in inflation, the
prime minister also asked the Budget Bureau to review other
projects.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay
Virawan said the economy would stabilize and liquidity would
improve if unproductive spending was slashed.  
