<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Asia's Giant Cities Facing Common Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Although culturally diverse, most
of Asia's giant cities are facing the same challenges -- more
slums, heavier traffic, further environmental degradation and a
continuous rise in social problems.
</P>
<P>
Experts warned that with the increasing urban concentration,
many giant cities in Asia are choking themselves to death if
municipal governments failed to take a new approach to development
and planning.
</P>
<P>
The warning sounds somewhat sensational, but the situation in
many Asian cities is really worrisome.
</P>
<P>
While Asia has maintained its position as the fastest growing
region in the world during the past decade, Asians have been
playing catch-up in the global game of urbanization, which has
attributed to the similar problems confronted by giant cities.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation could become even worse for giant cities
with more and more people pouring in. At present, there are only
13 cities in the world with a population of more than 10 million,
and seven of them are in Asia. But the Manila-based Asian
Development Bank predicted that there will be 27 megacities in the
world with 10 million or more people by 2015, and 17 of them will
be in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations' population forecasters said that over the
next 25 years, an extra 1.5 billion people will be added to the
one billion now living in Asia's crowded cities.
</P>
<P>
The immediate problem caused by the increasing urban
concentration is overcrowding. As the rural masses flood into the
cities in search of their fortune, they could hardly find proper
housing and have to live in shanty towns.
</P>
<P>
In metro Manila, a third of the population lives in shanties,
and in Dhaka, housing, water and power shortages are a fact of
life. It is said that more than half of city residents in the
region live in disease-ridden slums.
</P>
<P>
Overcrowding often means heavier traffic. In Bangkok, each day,
more than 760 new cars take to the road and the city's residents
make 18.87 million journeys on the average. As the traffic problem
is so awful in Bangkok, passengers carry portable toilets and
businessmen equip cars with faxes and mobile phones so they can
use them as "wheeled offices".
</P>
<P>
In the Malaysian capital of Kuala Lumpur, the traffic
congestion is rapidly approaching Bangkok's level. Recently, the
city has to open a multi-dollar electric rail network aimed at
reducing the inflow of traffic. There are seven million vehicles
on the road in Malaysia -- one vehicle for every three persons on
the average. And it was reported that some 250 people died in road
accidents in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Manila is no better than Bangkok and Kuala
Lumpur. Some 1.1 million motor vehicles are registered in Manila,
and 400,000 non-Manila registered vehicles enter the capital
during the day. During the rush hours, the traveling speed of a
motor vehicle is often limited to 20 kilometers per hour. One
often has to wait for more than half an hour to pass through a
road junction.
</P>
<P>
Overcrowding also means water shortage, severe environmental
degradation and more social problems. The United Nations Center
for Human Settlements predicted that extreme water shortage could
hit Bombay, Calcutta, Karachi, Jakarta, Beijing and Shanghai by
2010.
</P>
<P>
Without a revolution in urban problem-solving, more than 1.5
billion city dwellers in Asia "will face life-and
health-threatening environments by 2025," the U.N. organization
warned.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the water shortage and environmental degradation have
already threatened the life of city dwellers in some Asian cities.
Almost half of all infants in Manila are killed by pneumonia, the
leading killer of both adults and children in the Philippines.
Malnutrition and water-born disease are rife in the city's shanty
towns. Fouled water supply has become the city's number one
environmental problem.
</P>
<P>
A new World Bank study said that if India reduced air pollution
in its largest cities to meet the World Health Organization
standards, 40,000 premature deaths could be prevented every year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, with the increasing urban concentration, urban crimes
are up, and schools and hospitals are becoming more inadequate.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, municipal governments in Asia are well aware of
the challenges, and are looking for solutions to the city
problems. In some Asian cities, authorities are trying to find
ways to slow down the pace of urbanization, improve living
conditions of city residents and speed up the development of
infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
Experts expressed the hope that the municipal governments would
accept the challenges and turn the heavy pressure into concrete
actions to meet the challenges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Considers Amendment of Tariff Code System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is considering updating
its tariff code system to follow the new international practices,
a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Proposals on amending the country's customs tariff act to push
Thailand to follow the new code system adopted by the World
Customs Organization in 1996 are expected to be presented to the
cabinet for approval, the Bangkok Post said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand currently follows the 1988 version of the tariff code
system and it has to amend descriptions of 500 tariff items if it
wants to comply with the new code system which covers about 5,018
items, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Some Thai customs officials said that if Thailand followed the
new code, it would be easier for them to compare import and export
statistics with those of other countries.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is the only country in the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation group that has not yet adopted the 1996 code,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Thailand now faces some problems on joining the global
information technology agreement, while details of many items of
information products covered under the agreement are in the 1996
code system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
