<HEADLINE> NZ Plans to Lower Alcohol Limit for Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Government is
proposing tougher drunk-driving laws in a bid to further slash
road toll.
</P>
<P>
The measure is part of the coalition Government policies on
police and transport.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper The Evening Post quoted Minister of Health
Bill English as saying today the proposed law change was still in
its infancy and more details had to be worked through.
</P>
<P>
Police Commissioner Peter Doone said lowering the legal alcohol
limit was the shock motorists needed.
</P>
<P>
Although NZ's road toll recorded a low of 513 in last year
compared with 581 in 1995, too many motorists are still refusing
to accept anti-drink driving messages.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new laws will lower the legal limit from 80
milli-grams of alcohol per 100 milliliters of blood to 50
milligrams of alcohol per 100 milliliters of blood.  
</P>
