<HEADLINE> Prodi: Italians Ready to Make Sacrifices for Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Romano Prodi said
today that Italians are prepared to make sacrifices to bring
changes to the country so long as they are fair.
</P>
<P>
"It is useless to ignore the great novelties in the world, the
lengthening of life expectancy, the need to have a working life
completely different from that of the past," Prodi told reporters
here.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the budget deficit in public spending of 1996,
Prodi announced it did not affect the 1997 financial budget bill,
which has been approved by the parliament last December.
</P>
<P>
Asked how to solve the massive public spending, the focus of
public attention, Prodi said expenditure control is the only way,
promising not to impose new taxes.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the sensitive areas of pensions and the health
service will not be affected. Instead, they will be defended.
</P>
<P>
However, social welfare will be modernized and adapted to fit
the labor market, and existing problems will be immediately dealt
with, he added.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll issued today showed that half of the Italians
wish for tax cut, even if it may affect health care, education and
pension.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that the majority of people think the present
taxation is not only excessive and unjustified, but also
unbalanced, with wage-earners paying a greater proportion of their
incomes than the self-employed.
</P>
<P>
But people still show strong support for the government's fight
against tax evasion and a substantial majority oppose a tax
strike, as has been proposed by some businessmen in the north.
</P>
</TEXT>
