<HEADLINE> Mongolia to Spend 200 Million Dollars on Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Mongolian government
plans to invest more than 200 million U.S. dollars in 1997 to
upgrade the country's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The government will give top priority to fuel energy industry
in 1997 by renovating two power plants in Ulan Bator and coal
mines in Baganuur, said local press reports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the land-locked country will speed up the
development of its communications and transport industries.
</P>
<P>
Except a total of 1,190 kilometers asphalt-covered road, most
roads in Mongolia are covered with dirt. And the capital city of
Ulan Bator is often hit by power outage.
</P>
<P>
The poor overall infrastructure has been recognized as a major
obstacle in the way of the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, under a 10-year program, the government would put
aside 1 billion dollars for infrastructure buildup from 1995 to
2005. It spent 160 million dollars for the purpose in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A majority of the financing for infrastructure work would come
from loans and assistance provided by Japan, South Korea, Kuwait,
the Asian Development Bank and the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
