<HEADLINE> Peru's Foreign Reserves, GDP Increase in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Peru witnessed in 1996 an increase
in foreign exchange reserves to 8.54 billion U.S. dollars and a
growth of 2.2 percent in gross domestic product (GDP), showed
official statistics available today.
</P>
<P>
Banco Central de Reserva del Peru, the country's central bank,
said the reserves of hard currencies in last December were 118
million dollars higher than that in November, helping the whole
year's total mount to 1.89 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori said recently that he hoped
Peru's international reserves would reach 10 billion dollars
during the first semester of 1997.
</P>
<P>
As for GDP, figures from Peru's National Institute of
Statistics showed that it increased by 2.2 percent between January
and November in 1996 compared with the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Many sectors of the national economy, such as agriculture and
livestock, mining, manufacturing, electricity and water and
commerce, enjoyed moderate but steady growth during this period.
</P>
<P>
The GDP gain can mainly be attributed to the considerable
expansion in the manufacturing sector, which grew by 8.1 percent
as a result of the 79.4 percent increase in the output of fish
meals and fish oils.
</P>
<P>
The mild increase of Peru's GDP showed that the country
succeeded in cooling down its overheated economy when it saw a
record high of 12.9 percent GDP increase in 1994, followed by a
6.9 percent growth in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's per capita income remained static at
around 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian government managed to slow down the country's
paces of economic development in the second half of 1995 by
bringing down state investments, boosting exports and introducing
a tough plan of fiscal and monetary austerity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
