<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State to Give Stricter Control on Drug Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The central government will
scrutinize medicine quality more thoroughly this year to ensure
public safety, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Results of routine inspections will be published in media
reports, and business producing fake or substandard medicine will
be punished in line with state laws, said Shao Mingli, an official
with the Ministry of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
The ministry yesterday announced the lastest
inspection revealed 138 medicines failed to reach national
standards in 13 categories.
</P>
<P>
The inspection also found 48 fake medicines produced with
privated registration numbers from 26 factories, said Shao.
</P>
<P>
Some 96 factories produced substandard medicine. They were
ordered to improve their techniques and facilities immediately.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,100 medicines produced by 556 factories, 83 percent
met with the standards of the health ministry's National Institute
for Pharmaceutical and Biological Products Testing and Approving.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Health is urging hospitals and
pharmacies to stop selling the substandard and fake medicine and
asking them to report the products.
</P>
<P>
The state will conduct following-up inspections in the 96
problem factories, Shao said.
</P>
<P>
The State Pharmaceutical Administration revealed corruption
flourishes in the pharmaceutical industry, where kickbacks of up
to 25 percent are not uncommon. As a result, some pharmacies give
more consideration to the kickback than to quality.
</P>
<P>
A State Council circular in April 1996 called for a crack down
on sales commissions and illegal promotions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
