<HEADLINE> Death Toll From Disasters Plunges in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A total of 523 persons were
killed in 245 natural and man-made disasters that occurred in the
Philippines in 1996, a sharp decline from the death toll of 1,180
people in 1995, according to the country's disaster authorities.
</P>
<P>
In its year-end report, the National Disaster Coordinating
Council said 668 others were injured in the disasters in 1996,
compared to the 3,023 injuries in 343 natural and man-made
disasters in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of the 122 natural disasters that hit the country last year,
typhoons were the most destructive, killing 124 persons. Among the
123 man-made disasters, fire caused the highest number of
casualties, with at least 189 persons killed.
</P>
<P>
The report said that from January to November last year, there
were 31 devastating floods, 10 typhoons, 12 landslides, seven
tornadoes, 29 earthquakes, five red tide incidents and two
whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
The 123 major man-made disasters included 81 fire incidents, 11
civil disturbances, five sea mishaps, three ambuscades, two
vehicular accidents, six building accidents, and 15 bomb and
grenade explosions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Shows Teeth in Central Africa to Pressure Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- France has showed its teeth in the
Central African capital of Bangui in a reprisal operation against
the country's mutinous soldiers, by killing a dozen rebels and
ousting the latters from some of the strategic positions.
</P>
<P>
The operation, carried out on Sunday after two French soldiers
were murdered last Saturday in a rebel-controlled area of Bangui,
also came less than a month after President Jacques Chirac said at
a Franco-African summit that France would not take any part in the
conflict between the rebels and President Ange-Felix Patasse.
</P>
<P>
Local media said the operation means that the 2,300 French
troops -- reinforced by their fellow units from Chad and Djibouti
-- deployed in the African state have overpassed their original
mandate of maintaining peace and protecting European expatriates.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the French Socialist Party, Lionel Jospin, today
warned the government against engaging French soldiers into "the
military gearing" of Africa, and expressed his regret over the
deaths of both French and Africans in the violence of the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
France today reinforced its troops in Africa by sending two
more companies of the Third Regiment of Parachutists of Marine
Infantry from southern France to Chad, where France has been
keeping a 800-man "Epervier" task force since the 1980s to help
fend off Libyan troops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French troops handed over to Central African
paramilitary police 36 rebels taken prisoner in Sunday's assault,
which reportedly cost heavier casualties than what Paris claimed.
</P>
<P>
Local media quoted French Defense Ministry officials as saying
that from now on, France considers the only solution for the
on-going internal crisis in Central African Republic to be a total
and unconditional surrender of the rebels, whose number is unclear.
</P>
<P>
France is still giving a last chance to the rebels to
voluntarily give up their last stronghold and the French military
leaders have expressed their determination "not to let the
situation worsen" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Central African Republic is in the grip of the third mutiny
since 1996, in which soldiers of the Yokomas tribe of former
President Andre Kolingba are calling for the payment of their pay
arrears and the resignation of President Patasse, who came to
power in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Although Central Africa has France's second largest military
base in Africa after Djibouti bordering the Red Sea, the country
is also regarded as one of the high risk zones by the French
military, where there exist a tribal tension and non-stop
political intrigues since its independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
But France does not seem to be ready to give up its traditional
military and political privileges there, as the country is also a
pivoting station for France to carry out numerous military
interventions in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Such interventions include the "Epervier" and "Manta"
operations in Chad in the 1980s and the "Turquoise" operation in
Rwanda in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corrupt Senior Official of Hainan Expelled from The Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAINAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A leading provincial official in
China faces a criminal investigation after being expelled from the
Communist Party for taking bribes.
</P>
<P>
Wei Zefang, deputy-secretary of the Leading Party Members'
Group, and vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
Provincial People's Congress of Hainan Province, has been expelled
from the Party for taking bribes, the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection of the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee has announced.
</P>
<P>
"Wei took advantage of his power and twice accepted bribes
totalling 60,000 yuan (about 7,200 US dollars) while he was
holding the post of being member of the Standing Committee of the
Provincial Party Committee and deputy-secretary of the Party's
Provincial Political Science and Law Committee between 1992 and
1993," the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection said.
</P>
<P>
Based on the facts that Wei has violated the law and
discipline, the Standing Committee of the Provincial People's
Congress of Hainan has dismissed Wei from his job as vice-chairman
of the Standing Committee of the Provincial People's Congress, the
Central Commission for Discipline Inspection said.
</P>
<P>
"Since Wei has violated criminal law, the case has been handed
over to judicial departments and a criminal investigation against
him will be carried out," the Commission added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
