<HEADLINE> Russia to Save Money-Losing Siberian Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government is trying
to save the money-losing Baikal-Amur railway by boosting the
economic development in the regions along its route.
</P>
<P>
The 3,100-kilometer-long railway, which was built in the 1970s,
is the second artery running through the eastern Siberian and Far
Eastern regions.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of the transport ministry said the railway is
losing 120 billion rubles (21.5 million dollars) a month in its
operation.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry has been soliciting federal government
support in improving the investment environment and boosting the
economic development in the regions along the route.
</P>
<P>
A federal commission has also worked out a draft plan on the
establishment of special economic zones in these regions. 
</P>
