<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bolivia Assures No Hostage Swaps With MRTA Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Bolivian Foreign Minister
Antonio Aranibar said today there will be no swaps between the
four Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) guerrillas held in
Bolivia and the Bolivian ambassador to Peru who is now in the
guerrillas' hands.
</P>
<P>
Aranibar told reporters that Ambassador Jorge Gumucio Granier's
release will not be made in exchange for the release of four MRTA
guerrillas held in Bolivian prisons where they were well treated.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister is in Lima on a mission to negotiate the
release of its ambassador who has health problems. The Bolivian
ambassador is one of the 74 still being held hostage by the rebels
occupying the residence of Japan's ambassador in Lima.
</P>
<P>
The Bolivian foreign minister said that Ambassador Gumucio is
fine but was suffering diabetes and high blood pressure. Bolivia
is holding four Tupac Amaru guerrillas in jails for their
participation in the kidnapping of former Bolivian minister Samuel
Boria Medina, who is also an industrialist.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori this
afternoon, the Bolivian minister reaffirmed his country's
solidarity with Peru in the quest for a peaceful solution to the
current hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
Aranibar arrived in Lima on Sunday to express his government's
concern over the fate of Jorge Gumucio Granier, the Bolivian
ambassador to Peru and to negotiate his release.
</P>
<P>
The Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement commando has not made
any new releases since it released seven hostages on New Year's
Day.
</P>
<P>
There are still 74 hostages inside the residential compound of
the Japanese ambassador including Bolivian Ambassador Jorge
Gumucio and Japanese Ambassador Morihisa Aoki, Peruvian Foreign
Minister Francisco Tudel and Peruvian Agriculture Minister Rodolfo
Munante.
</P>
<P>
The MRTA commando that has been occupying the residence of the
Japanese Ambassador in Lima since December 17 insisted that all
its militants in Peruvian prisons must be set free before the
hostage crisis can be solved.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations between Peru and Uruguay deteriorated
after Uruguayan authorities released two members of the MRTA from
prison and the rebel commando allowed Ambassador Tabare Bocalandro
- who was once among the hostages - to leave.
</P>
<P>
The Bolivian government has refused to release the four MRTA
rebels who are serving sentences and has designated Eloy Avila as
acting ambassador to Peru.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Peruvian government is doing all it can to carry
out its official and public activities as usual.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Ecuadoran President Abdala Bucaram will
pay an official visit to Peru between January 13-15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
