<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ordinary People Have Few Complaints in Dalian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Unless Dalian's football team
hits a losing streak, residents in the most developed port city in
northeast China's Liaoning Province say they have few complaints.
</P>
<P>
People in coastal Dalian, the city renowned for its enthusiasm
for football, say their daily lives have improved as a result of
the local booming economy, more efficient government operations, a
higher living standard and a stabilized social security system.
</P>
<P>
As part of a nationwide drive to promote ethical and cultural
progress, the municipal government developed a strategy to first
tackle residents' everyday problems, then gradually work up to the
big issues.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, traffic was a headache for two million urban
residents. They were tired of the shortage of buses and bumpy city
roads.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government responded by investing 150 million
yuan (about 18 million US dollars) in road repairs, and added 26
one-way roads, covering a total length of 30 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
An advanced traffic-control system was brought into use in the
city, and public transport companies renovated 2,000 buses at a
cost of over 100 million yuan (12 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
By addressing the bottlenecked public transport, the government
has underscored building more houses and water facilities.
</P>
<P>
Dalian's developers have provided a 1.2 million square meter
residential compound, worth 1.6 billion yuan (190 million US
dollars), for 5,000 families suffering poor housing conditions.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 teacher families and doctoral scholars have
moved into five new buildings and two doctors' buildings in the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
In a move to alleviate water shortages in the city, the
government has accomplished a three-billion-yuan water supply
project, bringing 600,000 tons of clear water every day to
residents.
</P>
<P>
Problems with hospitals, nursery, primary and secondary
schools, which greatly affect the daily lives of ordinary people,
have also been resolved or greatly relieved.
</P>
<P>
In response to a government campaign for ethical and cultural
progress, residents in Dalian also shared the endeavor with their
own initiatives.
</P>
<P>
A recent achievement exhibition in the Xinghai Exhibition
Center received thousands of pieces of advice from the people,
including suggestions for more big sculptures in the city, more
entertainment facilities for senior citizens, and a symbolic
building for Dalian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
