<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Export-Import Bank Finances Power Plant Sale to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Export-Import Bank
said today it will offer a loan guarantee for the 19 million
U.S. dollars sale of gas and steam turbine generators to India.
</P>
<P>
The turbine generators will be made by the U.S.-based General
Electric Co. (GE) for the 60-megawatt combined cycle plant located
in the State of Gujarat on India's western coast.
</P>
<P>
While half of the world's power plants use coal, the GE
generators will involve a new clean coal technology known as
integrated gasification combined cycle (IGCC).
</P>
<P>
Through a coal gasification process, the IGCC process will
produce a clean gas from local lignite coal, and the gas then will
be burned in the plant's gas turbine to make electricity.
</P>
<P>
The Export-Import Bank, based in this U.S. capital city, is a
governmental agency that assists financing and promoting sales of
U.S. goods and services abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
