<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Students to Obtain More Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 7 (Xinhua) -- China's largest education
charity, the "Hope Project", has decided to increase its financial
subsidy to poor students, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that beginning September 1, 1997, each
beneficiary will receive 50 yuan (six US dollars) per semester
instead of the previous 40 yuan (4.80 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to help poor students, mainly living in
poverty-stricken rural areas, buy textbooks.
</P>
<P>
When the project was launched in 1989, the per term aid was 20
yuan (2.40 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Price hike is the the main factor for the China Youth
Development Foundation, the non-governmental sponsor of the
project, to set the new rate, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In the past seven years, the project has prevented 1.2 million
children from quitting school, with donations of 800 million yuan
(96 million US dollars) it received from home and abroad,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that about 30 million children aged
between six and 14 have never been to school, or they have quit
school because they could not pay the tuition fees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
