<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Coconut Exports Drop Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines, the world's
largest exporter of coconut products, exported 845.4 million U.S.
dollars worth of coconut products in 1996, a sharp drop from the
recorded 1.1 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the coconut export income last year is still the second
highest in the last 15 years, local press reports said today,
citing figures released by the Philippine Coconut Authority.
</P>
<P>
The drop in coconut exports receipts resulted from a huge
decline in the sale of coconut oil last year to 588 million
dollars from 842 million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Volume of coconut products exported also declined by 39 percent
from 2.3 million metric tons in 1995 to 1.5 million metric tons
this year.
</P>
<P>
Coconut authority administrator Virgilio David expected coconut
exports to reach the level of 1.1 billion dollars in 1997, with
recovering coconut production in the country and growing demand in
overseas markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investments Help Economic Growth in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Cuban government
official today attributed part of his country's 7.8 percent growth
of gross domestic product (GDP) in 1996 to foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Ferradaz, Cuba's minister of foreign investment and
economic collaboration, said the capital inflow last year "in one
way or another" contributed to the annual economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The GDP gain, he noted, was achieved amid many adverse
conditions, such as the Helms-Burton Act approved on March 12 by
U.S. Congress for tightening the sanction against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign investors took maximum advantage of the
Caribbean island nation's skilled labor force, adequate
infrastructure and favorable policies, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The number of Cuba-foreign businesses operating in the country
increased to 260 in 1996, compared with 240 by the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The average economic growth was 3.5 percent throughout Latin
America last year, Ferradaz said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
