<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Flood in Northwest, Snow in South in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Surging water broke through
another levee today and officials warned of more flooding in
Northern California while heavy snow falls in the southern U.S.,
blocking highways and forcing schools to close.
</P>
<P>
There were six levee breaks near Manteca on the San Joaquin
River, with the latest at 3 a.m. local time today. About 400
people had evacuated but some 1,500 remained in a recommended
evacuation area, said the Office of Emergency Services in
California.
</P>
<P>
With constant pressure from runoff pouring out of the Sierra
Nevada, fragile levees are threatened to break out, local
officials warned.
</P>
<P>
Although 23,000 people were allowed to return to homes in Yuba
and Sutter counties, about 160 kilometers northeast of San
Francisco Sunday, many of the 90,000 people fled home Thursday
were still out after a levee break there.
</P>
<P>
A week of snow and rain devastated areas of Washington, Oregon,
Idaho and western Nevada. Up to 40 inches of rain fell on the
region and rising temperatures melted dense snow in the Sierra
Nevada, leading to flooding.
</P>
<P>
At least 29 deaths have been blamed on the flooding and storms
in California, Washington, Idaho and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people from the California Conservation Corps
hauled sandbags and laid plastic along levees on Sacramento County
islands and along the San Joaquin River.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than a foot of snow dumped on the mountains of
Arizona and New Mexico this morning and closed schools and
highways.
</P>
<P>
The storm in the Southwest was scattering snow and light rain
across parts of northern Arizona and New Mexico, southern Colorado
and parts of western Texas.
</P>
<P>
Up to 14 inches of snow had fallen in 24 hours on northern
Arizona's high San Francisco peaks. In some New Mexico's mountain
areas, snow piled up to 16 inches.
</P>
<P>
Blowing snow and ice-covered pavement this morning closed
interstate highways in the region and schools were closed in more
than a dozen New Mexico cities.
</P>
<P>
Snow also was possible into Oklahoma, with rain likely across
the southern half of Texas and into Louisiana today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
