<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- New figures showing the biggest monthly current account
deficit in a year and the weakest demand for labor in almost three
years have highlighted Australia's two outstanding economic
problems: low national saving and high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The Federal Government is being confronted with a new
dilemma in managing the economy in 1997, with the worst job
prospects in three years coinciding with Australia's trade
position diving deeper into deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The world's most famous indigenous rights activist, South
Africa's President Nelson Mandela has been asked to Australia by
the Council for Aboriginal Reconciliation to celebrate the 30th
anniversary of the 1967 referendum recognizing aborigines as
citizens.
</P>
<P>
The Australian financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- A slide in export earnings pushed the monthly current
account deficit to its highest point for a year in November.
Balance of payments figures for the month showed a current account
shortfall of 1.92 billion Australian dollars (1.53 billion US
dollars) after seasonal adjustment.  
</P>
