<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbian Parties Urges Peaceful Solution to Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the opposition
Serbian Radical Party Vojislav Seselj said today that Serbs should
settle their disagreements and crucial political issues peacefully
and without foreign powers' interference.
</P>
<P>
The Serb people must handle their internal problems without
foreign interference, Seselj said, referring to the foreign powers
"which have proved their hostility towards the Serbian people by
bombing towns, villages, schools and hospitals throughout the
Bosnian Serb territories during the civil war and by imposing
economic sanctions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO forces bombed Bosnian Serb military installations in
early September 1995 to retaliate the alleged killing of 37
Sarajevo civilians by shelling the city on August 28. The Serb
authorities claimed scores of people had been killed during NATO's
massive air raid.
</P>
<P>
"In 1997, we must do all in our best to reduce internal
conflicts and tensions so as not to resolve our political disputes
and problems in bloody showdowns in the streets of Serbian towns,
but through a dialogue between national representatives in the
Serbian and Yugoslav parliaments," Seselj said in his Christmas
and New Year message which was released by the Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Western countries have warned Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic not to use force against the anti-government protests or
would face international isolation and sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Alsos today, the Nikola Pasic Radical Party called on the
Serbian government to act in the interest of the Serbian people
and "energetically prevent an open aggression by outside
aggressors and inside servants against the republic, the
constitution and freedom of the Serbian people."
</P>
<P>
"The engagement of the Zajedno (Together) coalition, united
with ethnic Albanian separatists and Western principals, continues
working on the destabilization of Serbia and its reduction" to a
region around Belgrade, the party said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The United Radical Party of Serbia also described today as
impermissible the foreign interferences into a sovereign state's
internal affairs, and especially the dictating of conditions for
resolving internal problems.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that state organs and institutions enable normal
work and normal life in all Serbian cities and towns, which the
current events have rendered impossible," Tanjug quoted the
party's statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
After 48 consecutive days of peaceful demonstrations, the
Zajedno coalition organized automobile protest Sunday, during
which many cars drove slowly in downtown Belgrade to block the
traffic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
