<HEADLINE> Irish PM Condemns IRA's Rocket Attack in Belfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister John Bruton
issued an "unreserved condemnation" today about a rocket attack on
the High Court in Belfast by the Irish Republican Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
Bruton said the IRA had shown a disregard for the wishes of all
people in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Patrick Mayhew warned the IRA they
cannot bomb their way to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The tactic would never get the IRA's "political party" into
talks, he told the BBC. "It simply reinforces their self-imposed
exclusion," he added.
</P>
<P>
President Gerry Adams of Sinn Fien, the IRA's political party,
also said today the IRA rocket attack at the Belfast High Court
was a "regrettable" symptom of problems which must be tackled.
</P>
