<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Employers Warned on Attitude to Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- British employers' attitude
toward training should be changed if Britain's labor market is to
produce the skills required by a global economy, said a study
published today by the Department for Education and Employment.
</P>
<P>
The study said that more flexible working has brought cost and
efficiency gains for employers, and the choice of different life
style for employees.
</P>
<P>
However, the new, flexible labor market holds a bleak future
for the less well qualified, as employers remain reluctant to
spend money on training staff who are likely to switch jobs at an
increasing rate.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve continuous improvement in work performance,
employees need to acquire progressive skills to improve their
competences outside their current organization, the study added.
</P>
<P>
In fact, "for some 70 percent of those at work, the end of
jobs-for-life has not been accompanied by training in those core
skills required by the new culture of high performance dictated by
globalization," said Amin Rajan, principal author of the report.
</P>
<P>
The study said that rapid changes in technology and working
methods require the education and training systems to be far more
responsive than they currently are in Britain.
</P>
<P>
It concluded that the burden of responsibility for developing
personal competences currently rests with the individual and
public bodies. Employers need to be equal partners in the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Paper Urges US to Pay Dues to UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The New York Times today
urged the U.S. government to pay its outstanding contributions to
the United Nations as Kofi Annan, who is highly respected in
Washington and elsewhere, has taken the office of UN
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
An editorial of the paper said that withholding the dues was
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
The editorial noted that some Congressional Republicans are
unwilling to pay the debt until Annan carries out major structural
reforms.
</P>
<P>
"The (Clinton) Administration, while continuing to press
vigorously for reform, must make good on its implicit promise and
persuade Congress to pay up now," the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
Although more needs to be done to reform the UN, Boutros
Boutros-Ghali did more than any other secretary-general. He cut
the New York staff by one-third. He created the office of the
inspector general, which has uncovered and corrected inefficiency.
He installed Joseph Connor, an American who formerly led the
accounting firm of Price Waterhouse, as chief financial officer,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Annan's task is to build on these achievements. "More important
than simply shrinking the UN, however, is making it more effective
in a world where the end of the cold war changed many things," the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Though Annan brings considerable strengths to the task of
reform, his reach is limited, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Reforming the UN requires the cooperation of its members, and
the United States can help now by paying its dues, the editorial
said in conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi, Mobutu Reaffirm Territorial Integrity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Zaire reiterated
today their commitment to the maintenance of their territorial
integrity and world-recognized boundaries, the Kenya Television
Network (KTN) reported.
</P>
<P>
"These principles are unnegotiable," said a joint communique
issued after today's summit between Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi and his Zairean counterpart Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
They expressed regret for a U.N. resolution on deploying a
multi-national force in the eastern Zaire, said the KTN report.
</P>
<P>
The Moi-Mobutu talks, described as "fruitful" by Kenyan
officials, also focused on the crisis in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
However, Moi made no remarks when returning from the central
African country.
</P>
<P>
Moi, as well as Ugandan, Tanizanian and other African
leaders, were mandated by the December Nairobi summit to take
necessary steps to end the conflict in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
