<DOCNO> XIE19970107.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Criticizes Cyprus for Missile Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
today criticized Cyprus for a deal with Russia in which Moscow
will provide advanced anti-aircraft missiles for the defense of
the Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
It said the provision of Russian SA-10 missile systems with 144
kilometer range would destabilize the balance of power in Cyprus
and harm efforts to broker a peace agreement between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"The United States regrets this step. We believe this will
complicate efforts to achieve a lasting peace in Cyprus... and the
purchase introduces a new and destabilizing element on this
island," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the top American envoy in Cyprus, Kenneth Brill,
lodged a formal protest with President Glafcos Clerides, and
American diplomats also "expressed disappointment" with the
missile sale during meetings with Russian Foreign Ministry
officials in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the lasting security and peace for the
Mediterranean island could only be achieved at the bargaining
table with all sides committed to finding a solution.
</P>
<P>
"The past has shown that importing weapons has brought only
arms increase from the other sides. This new missile system
threatens to take the arms buildup on Cyprus to a new and
disturbing qualitative level," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
