<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Kohl Insist on Scheduled NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today agreed that the expansion
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) should proceed on
the timetable outlined by the organization's foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"They exchanged views on how that will happen in the context of
the very important discussions going on between NATO and the
Russian Federation, related to the NATO-Russia charter," White
House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
In their half-hour conversation, the two leaders also discussed
Kohl's recent visit to Russia, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
During his Russia tour last Saturday, Kohl talked with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin on the NATO expansion. The latter
expressed Russia's concern over planned NATO expansion to include
former Soviet bloc countries.
</P>
<P>
The NATO foreign ministers agreed last month to issue
invitations for the first former Soviet bloc countries to join the
alliance at a July summit in Madrid, Spain, and to admit them by
1999, the organization's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has strongly opposed NATO's eastward expansion plans,
which Russia sees as a threat to its security.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton and Kohl discussed in general Russia's
concerns regarding expansion. "There's certainly a great deal of
concern -- some would say a certain degree of ambivalence -- on
that subject, and the West is well aware of that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin are scheduled to meet in March at an
undetermined location in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
