<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Rise on Wall Street Revival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Major European share markets all
ended higher today, supported by a rebound on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Dow's recent sharp swings and concerns on
interest rates rise kept them from rising further up.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London closed slightly higher, with the FTSE
100 index 17 points up at 4,106.5, but off last week's peaks, as
the market largely ignored another strong performance on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that many investors seemed prepared to sit it out,
unnerved by fears of higher interest rates on both sides of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
Post-holiday torppor dominated the market and trade volumes
were thin as investors feared more Wall Street volatility.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, stocks closed higher in line with strong gains in
the rest of the world's markets, with the DAX-30 index up 22.04
points at 2,881.32.
</P>
<P>
However, weaker bonds gave a limit to the market's upside,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street's surge Friday and hopes of continued French
interest rates cuts gave a boost to the French stock market
despite reservations over the economy and the franc's strength,
and the CAC-40 index finished 23.91 points up at 2,306.67.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 leading British shares index ended 17 points
higher at 4,106.5. In Frankfurt, the DAX-30 index closed 22.04
points up at 2,881.32. The Paris CAC-40 index finished up 23.91
points at 2,306.67. 
</P>
</TEXT>
