<HEADLINE> Dow Sets New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average flirted with the 6,600 mark today as stocks extended their
rally from last week despite growing uncertainty about several
economic reports due out later this week.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip gauge was up as much as 75 points earlier,
surpassing 6,600 for the first time, before falling back to a gain
of 23.09 to 6,567.18, enough to break the record set on December
27 at 6,560.91.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 527.10
million shares, much higher than 451.95 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures also pulled back with bonds as rising oil
prices aggravated renewed inflation concerns.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 0.36 to 747.67, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 0.22 to 394.28.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 5.74 to 1,316.42, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 0.39 to 572.06.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
rose from late Friday's 6.73 percent to 6.77 percent, the high
level since late October.
</P>
<P>
Early indications on the holiday shopping season remained
discouraging.
</P>
<P>
Strong technology shares initially extended Friday's
market-leading advance, but then succumbed to profit-taking.
</P>
</TEXT>
