<HEADLINE> 30 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces killed
30 rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in the
last 24 hours of military operations in southeastern Turkey, the
state-run TRT radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the security forces staged the military
operations against the PKK militants on the Cudi Mountain in
Sirnak province bordering northern Iraq under the cover of Turkish
fighters and assault helicopters.
</P>
<P>
One soldier of the security forces also died in the
operations, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report added that the security forces had captured 50
alleged PKK sympathizers during the operations in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Turkish government troops have been conducting
the cross-border military operations against the PKK camps in
northern Iraq since December 30, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The PKK makes use of the bases in northern Iraq over which
Baghdad has lost control in its guerrilla war for autonomy in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish government troops have crossed into northern Iraq
several times to wipe out the PKK rebels, who intermittently
launch cross-border raids against Turkish targets.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has protested against the Turkish
cross-border military operations, accusing Turkey of violating
its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
In the past ten years, the Turkish security forces have killed
13,255, injured 244 and captured 2,000 of the PKK militants,
dealing a heavy blow to the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
In all, over 21,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops have been killed in the conflicts since August
1984 when the PKK began fighting in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
