<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Praises Police for Arresting Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today commended police officers who swiftly
apprehended suspects for the three bomb attacks around Rustenburg
in North-West Province on Sunday, said reports reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement from the presidental office in Pretoria,
Mandela expressed his satisfaction over the progress made in the
investigations, and he is confident the culprits will be
brought to be punished to the full extent of the law.
</P>
<P>
"There is no excuse whatsoever in our democracy for anyone to
seek to pursue political aims by violent means," said Mandela,
adding those responsible will face the full might of South
Africa's democratically elected and legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
The President also expressed his profound sympathies with the
families and communities which had fallen victims to the bomb
attakcs.
</P>
<P>
Three bombs went off in Rustenburg Sunday morning, causing two
injuries and a considerable damage to the three targeted sites,
including a mosque.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, police arrested a rightwing suspect they
believed could help them with their investigations into the
Christmas Eve bomb attack on a Worcester shopping mall near Cape
Town, leaving four dead and more than 60 injuries.
</P>
<P>
De Wet, 41, arrested for being in possession of a stolen
vehicle, is one of the three rightwing members who escaped from
a prison last March while standing trial for their part in a
Johannesburg bombing spree that killed at least 20 people on the
eve of the April 1994 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Two other suspects were already arrested on Sunday near
Rustenburg for their alleged involvement in the bomb blasts in
the area, added the source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
