<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) --The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's state-owned oil company, TPAO, is expected
to join an international consortium to exploit oil in Sudanese
waters in the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has signed a preliminary agreement with the
Sudanese government to exploit the country's rich oil reserves in
the Red Sea, the local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Details of the agreement will be worked out in March
by a joint economic commission between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Other members of the consortium will be determined in the
upcoming months.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The first conference of businessmen in Arab states
opened here today, which is aimed at enabling the private sector
in the Arab world to boost cooperation and coordination in the
whole Arab economy.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 businessmen from various Arab countries
participated in the gathering, which will last three days.
</P>
<P>
The conference was organized by the Jordanian and Egyptian
Businessmen Associations.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- About 348.9 million Jordan dinars (about 492.8
million U.S. dollars) were invested in 254 new projects in Jordan
in 1996, according to a latest report from the Investment
Promotion Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The report said that this represented a 26 percent increase
over 1995. The building of 40 hotels are also included in the new
projects.
</P>
<P>
Other projects were in agricultural, medical and maritime
transport and railway sectors.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is trying to attract new investments by offering up
to 75 percent tax reductions for businesses.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's natural gas production has increased from 2.2
billion cubic meters in 1981 to around 13 billion cubic meters in
1996, local English language newspaper Egyptian Gazette reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Oil Hamdy el-Banbi revealed Sunday while
inaugurating a 100-million-U.S.-dollar natural gas project in Port
Said, a Mediterranean coastal city 210 kilometers northeast of
Cairo, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The first stage of the project will provide about 10,000
housing units and 20 industrial and commercial institutions with
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The second stage, which will start next July, will include
providing 130,000 housing units and 200 industrial institutions with
natural gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
