<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Salvation Council Calls for Humanitarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Somali National
Salvation Council, formed Friday by 26 Somali factions, called
today for extended international humanitarian aid to the East
African country.
</P>
<P>
"Somalia is facing a new humanitarian plight characterised by
new famine, hardship and other sufferings," said the five
co-chairmen of the 11-member executive committee of the council
at their first press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The Chairmen are Mudane Abdulahi Yusuf Ahmed, Mudane Ali Mahdi
Mohammed, Abdelkalid Aden Mohammed, Aden Abdule Noor and Osman
Ali Att.
</P>
<P>
"We need an urgent infusion of humanitarian aid to our people
and our country so that lives could be saved," they said.
</P>
<P>
The chairmen also urged the international community to help
establish a transitional central authority or a provisional
central government in a war-torn Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The council is planning to set up a transitional government,
draft a national transitional chapter, pave a way for inter-clan
reconciliation, and organize a national reconciliation conference
in Bossasso, Somalia within the next six months.
</P>
<P>
The council will also set up a liason bureau in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The council chairmen called on Hussein Aideed, the powerful
warlord who, hoping to become the Somali president, had been
boycotting the council, to take part in such a national build-up.
"The door is still open," they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
